export const RT_ENCYCLOPEDIA_SUPPLEMENTARY: RtEncyclopediaEntry[] = [

  // ═══ COPD Management (8 more) ═══
  {slug:"oxygen-induced-hypercapnia",title:"Oxygen-Induced Hypercapnia in COPD",category:"COPD Management",seoTitle:"Oxygen-Induced Hypercapnia – Why O2 Raises CO2 in COPD | RRT",seoDescription:"Understand oxygen-induced hypercapnia mechanisms: Haldane effect, V/Q mismatch, and hypoxic drive theory for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["oxygen induced hypercapnia","Haldane effect","COPD oxygen","hypoxic drive","V/Q mismatch","RRT exam"],overview:"Excessive oxygen supplementation in COPD patients can paradoxically worsen hypercapnia. While traditionally attributed to suppression of hypoxic ventilatory drive, the primary mechanisms are actually the Haldane effect and release of hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction causing increased V/Q mismatch.",mechanismPhysiology:"Three mechanisms contribute: (1) Haldane effect (most important): oxygenated hemoglobin binds less CO2, displacing CO2 from hemoglobin into plasma, raising PaCO2. (2) V/Q mismatch: oxygen relieves hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction in poorly ventilated areas, redirecting blood flow to regions that cannot adequately exchange CO2. (3) Reduced ventilatory drive: while real, this accounts for only a small portion of the CO2 rise. Studies show minute ventilation decreases only modestly with O2 supplementation in COPD.",clinicalRelevance:"Target SpO2 88–92% in COPD exacerbation per BTS guidelines. The DECAF trial and Austin et al. demonstrated that titrated O2 (targeting 88–92%) reduced mortality compared to high-flow O2 in COPD patients. Use Venturi mask for precise FiO2 delivery when controlling oxygenation in COPD.",signsSymptoms:"Signs of oxygen-induced hypercapnia: increasing somnolence, confusion, headache, flushed skin after starting or increasing O2, rising PaCO2 on serial ABGs despite stable clinical picture, CO2 narcosis in severe cases.",assessment:"Monitor ABG 30–60 minutes after starting O2 or changing FiO2. Track PaCO2 trend. Assess mental status serially. If PaCO2 rises significantly with worsening acidosis, consider NIV rather than simply reducing O2 (the patient still needs oxygenation).",management:"Titrate O2 to SpO2 88–92% using Venturi mask for precision. If hypercapnia worsens despite controlled O2: initiate NIV (BiPAP). Do NOT withhold O2 from a hypoxemic COPD patient due to fear of hypercapnia — hypoxemia kills faster than hypercapnia. The solution is controlled O2 delivery plus ventilatory support, not O2 avoidance.",complications:"CO2 narcosis, respiratory arrest if excessive O2 suppresses drive in a patient dependent on hypoxic drive, delayed recognition if ABGs not monitored after O2 changes.",clinicalPearls:["The Haldane effect is the primary mechanism of O2-induced hypercapnia, not just hypoxic drive suppression","NEVER withhold O2 from a hypoxemic patient — hypoxemia is more immediately dangerous than hypercapnia","Target SpO2 88–92% and use ABG monitoring to guide therapy","If PaCO2 rises: add NIV, don't simply reduce O2"],examPitfalls:["Attributing O2-induced hypercapnia solely to hypoxic drive suppression — Haldane effect is the major contributor","Withholding oxygen from a hypoxemic COPD patient due to CO2 concerns","Not monitoring ABG after changing FiO2 in a COPD patient"],faqJson:[{question:"Why does oxygen raise CO2 in COPD patients?",answer:"Primarily through the Haldane effect (oxygenated Hb releases CO2) and worsened V/Q mismatch (relief of hypoxic vasoconstriction), with a minor contribution from reduced ventilatory drive."},{question:"Should oxygen be withheld from hypoxemic COPD patients?",answer:"Never. Hypoxemia is more immediately dangerous than hypercapnia. The correct approach is controlled O2 delivery (SpO2 88–92%) with ventilatory support (NIV) if hypercapnia worsens."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["COPD Management","Oxygen Therapy"]},
  {slug:"copd-inhaler-devices",title:"Inhaler Devices & Technique in COPD",category:"COPD Management",seoTitle:"Inhaler Devices – MDI, DPI, SMI & Nebulizer Technique | RRT",seoDescription:"Compare inhaler devices for COPD: MDI with spacer, DPI, SMI, nebulizer. Proper technique and device selection for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["MDI","DPI","SMI","nebulizer","inhaler technique","spacer","COPD inhalers","RRT exam"],overview:"Inhaler device selection and proper technique significantly impact drug delivery and clinical outcomes. Up to 80% of patients use their inhalers incorrectly, making technique education a critical respiratory therapy function. Available devices include metered-dose inhalers (MDIs), dry powder inhalers (DPIs), soft mist inhalers (SMIs), and nebulizers.",mechanismPhysiology:"MDI: pressurized canister releases a metered dose of medication propelled by HFA propellant. Requires coordination of actuation and inhalation (slow, deep breath). Spacer/valved holding chamber (VHC) eliminates coordination need, reduces oropharyngeal deposition. DPI: breath-actuated, no propellant — requires rapid, forceful inhalation to disaggregate powder. SMI (Respimat): liquid medication produces a slow-moving aerosol cloud for 1.5 seconds, requiring less inspiratory effort. Nebulizer: converts liquid medication to aerosol using compressed gas (jet) or mesh membrane (vibrating mesh).",clinicalRelevance:"Device selection should match patient capability: MDI+spacer for most patients (reduces coordination difficulty), DPI for patients with adequate inspiratory flow (avoid in severe COPD with very low inspiratory flow), SMI for elderly or those with poor hand strength/coordination, nebulizer for patients unable to use handheld devices (very elderly, severe dyspnea, cognitive impairment). Minimizing the number of different device types improves technique retention.",signsSymptoms:"Poor technique indicators: hearing the medication spray without inhalation (MDI), no powder taste (DPI — inadequate flow), quick shallow breathing with MDI (should be slow and deep), failure to shake MDI, failure to prime new inhalers.",assessment:"Assess technique at every visit using a standardized checklist for each device type. Common MDI errors: not shaking, not using spacer, breathing too fast, not holding breath 10 seconds, not waiting between puffs. Common DPI errors: exhaling into device (causes clumping), inadequate inspiratory force, not loading dose properly.",management:"Teach correct technique using teach-back method: demonstrate, have patient return-demonstrate, correct errors. MDI+spacer: shake, exhale, place spacer in mouth, actuate and begin slow deep inhalation, hold breath 10 seconds, wait 30–60 seconds between puffs. DPI: load dose, exhale away from device, rapid forceful inhalation through mouthpiece, hold breath 10 seconds. All devices: rinse mouth after ICS to prevent thrush.",complications:"Poor technique: underdosing (treatment failure), oropharyngeal deposition (thrush with ICS, cough), worsening symptoms despite prescribed medications. Device-related: MDI propellant sensitivity (rare), DPI clumping with moisture exposure.",clinicalPearls:["Check inhaler technique at EVERY visit — it is the most common cause of 'treatment failure'","MDI WITHOUT spacer deposits ~80% of medication in the oropharynx, only ~10% reaches the lungs","DPIs require inspiratory flow ≥ 30 L/min — may not be suitable for patients with severe obstruction","Minimize the number of different device types to improve technique retention"],examPitfalls:["Not using a spacer with MDI — dramatically reduces lung deposition","Recommending DPI for a patient with very low inspiratory flow (severe COPD)","Not checking inhaler technique when a patient reports worsening symptoms"],faqJson:[{question:"Why should a spacer be used with an MDI?",answer:"A spacer eliminates the need for hand-breath coordination, reduces oropharyngeal deposition by 50–80%, and increases lung deposition of the medication."},{question:"When should a nebulizer be used instead of a handheld inhaler?",answer:"Nebulizers are appropriate for patients unable to use handheld devices: very elderly, severely dyspneic patients, those with cognitive impairment, or during acute exacerbations when coordination is impaired."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["COPD Management","Pharmacology"]},
  {slug:"copd-cor-pulmonale",title:"Cor Pulmonale in COPD",category:"COPD Management",seoTitle:"Cor Pulmonale – Right Heart Failure in COPD | RRT Encyclopedia",seoDescription:"Learn cor pulmonale: chronic hypoxia causing pulmonary hypertension and right heart failure in COPD for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["cor pulmonale","right heart failure","pulmonary hypertension","COPD","hypoxic vasoconstriction","RRT exam"],overview:"Cor pulmonale is right ventricular hypertrophy and eventual failure caused by pulmonary hypertension secondary to chronic lung disease. In COPD, chronic hypoxemia triggers sustained hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction, increasing pulmonary vascular resistance and overloading the right ventricle.",mechanismPhysiology:"Chronic hypoxemia → sustained hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction → pulmonary arterial remodeling (smooth muscle hypertrophy, intimal fibrosis) → fixed pulmonary hypertension → increased RV afterload → RV hypertrophy → eventual RV dilation and failure. Additional contributors: destruction of pulmonary vascular bed (emphysema), polycythemia (increased blood viscosity from chronic hypoxia), and hyperinflation (compresses pulmonary vessels).",clinicalRelevance:"Cor pulmonale develops in 25–30% of COPD patients and is associated with significant morbidity and mortality. The most effective treatment is long-term oxygen therapy (LTOT), which reduces hypoxic vasoconstriction and slows disease progression. Cor pulmonale or polycythemia (Hct > 56%) are qualifying conditions for home O2 at higher PaO2 thresholds (56–59 mmHg).",signsSymptoms:"Right heart failure signs: peripheral edema (ankle and pretibial), elevated JVP, hepatomegaly, hepatojugular reflux, S3 gallop, loud P2 (pulmonic valve closure), tricuspid regurgitation murmur, ascites (late). ECG: right axis deviation, P pulmonale (peaked P waves), RV hypertrophy pattern. CXR: enlarged right heart border, prominent pulmonary arteries.",assessment:"Assess for peripheral edema, JVP elevation, hepatomegaly. Echocardiography: RV dilation, tricuspid regurgitation, estimated RVSP (pulmonary artery systolic pressure > 35 mmHg suggests PH). ABG: chronic respiratory acidosis with compensated metabolic alkalosis. BNP/NT-proBNP may be elevated. Monitor SpO2 at rest, with activity, and during sleep.",management:"Primary: LTOT (≥ 15 hours/day) to relieve hypoxic vasoconstriction — the only treatment proven to improve survival. Diuretics: furosemide for fluid overload. Optimize COPD therapy: bronchodilators, smoking cessation, pulmonary rehabilitation. Avoid excessive supplemental O2 (target SpO2 88–92%). Phlebotomy if Hct > 65% with symptoms. Avoid CCBs (unlike idiopathic PAH, they are not effective and may worsen V/Q mismatch in COPD-related PH).",complications:"Right heart failure progression, fluid overload, hepatic congestion, renal impairment, cardiac arrhythmias (especially atrial fibrillation), reduced exercise capacity, increased mortality.",clinicalPearls:["LTOT is the primary treatment for cor pulmonale — reduces hypoxic vasoconstriction","Cor pulmonale is a qualifying condition for home O2 at PaO2 56–59 mmHg","Diuretics help fluid overload but treat the symptom, not the cause — O2 therapy is essential","Avoid CCBs in COPD-related pulmonary hypertension — they worsen V/Q mismatch"],examPitfalls:["Treating COPD-related PH with calcium channel blockers (only effective in vasoreactive idiopathic PAH)","Not prescribing LTOT for COPD patients with cor pulmonale","Forgetting that Hct > 56% qualifies patients for home O2 at higher PaO2 thresholds"],faqJson:[{question:"What causes cor pulmonale in COPD?",answer:"Chronic hypoxemia triggers sustained hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction, leading to pulmonary hypertension, right ventricular hypertrophy, and eventually right heart failure."},{question:"What is the best treatment for cor pulmonale?",answer:"Long-term oxygen therapy (≥ 15 hours/day) is the most effective treatment, as it reduces hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction and is the only intervention proven to improve survival."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["COPD Management","Critical Care"]},
  {slug:"copd-smoking-cessation",title:"Smoking Cessation in COPD",category:"COPD Management",seoTitle:"Smoking Cessation – Most Important COPD Intervention | RRT",seoDescription:"Smoking cessation strategies for COPD: pharmacotherapy (NRT, varenicline, bupropion), counseling, and the 5 A's framework for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["smoking cessation","COPD","nicotine replacement","varenicline","5 A's","RRT exam"],overview:"Smoking cessation is the single most effective intervention to slow COPD progression. It is the ONLY measure proven to reduce the accelerated decline in FEV1 in COPD patients. Respiratory therapists play a key role in brief interventions, counseling referral, and pharmacotherapy recommendation using the 5 A's framework (Ask, Advise, Assess, Assist, Arrange).",mechanismPhysiology:"Cigarette smoke contains >7,000 chemicals including oxidants, carcinogens, and particulate matter that cause chronic airway inflammation, mucous gland hypertrophy, ciliary dysfunction, and progressive alveolar destruction. Nicotine addiction involves dopamine reward pathways — physical withdrawal peaks at 3–5 days and subsides over 2–4 weeks. Psychological dependence persists longer. After cessation: FEV1 decline returns to normal rate (but lost function is not recovered), cardiovascular risk decreases, exacerbation frequency reduces.",clinicalRelevance:"The Lung Health Study demonstrated that sustained smoking cessation significantly slows FEV1 decline compared to continued smoking. Combining pharmacotherapy with counseling doubles quit rates compared to either alone. All respiratory therapists should routinely apply the 5 A's framework: Ask about smoking at every visit, Advise to quit, Assess readiness, Assist with cessation plan, Arrange follow-up.",signsSymptoms:"Nicotine withdrawal: irritability, anxiety, difficulty concentrating, increased appetite, insomnia, cravings, depressed mood. Symptoms peak at 2–3 days and resolve over 2–4 weeks with pharmacotherapy support.",assessment:"Assess: smoking status (current, former, never), pack-years (packs/day × years smoked), readiness to quit (precontemplation, contemplation, preparation, action, maintenance — Stages of Change model), prior quit attempts and what helped/failed, triggers for smoking, level of nicotine dependence (Fagerström scale).",management:"Pharmacotherapy (first-line): NRT (patch, gum, lozenge, inhaler, nasal spray — can combine patch + short-acting form), varenicline (Chantix — most effective single agent, 30% quit rate vs 15% placebo), bupropion (Wellbutrin — also helps with depression and weight gain). Counseling: individual or group behavioral support, quitline referral, motivational interviewing for ambivalent patients. Combine pharmacotherapy + counseling for best results. E-cigarettes: not FDA-approved for cessation; harm reduction potential debated.",complications:"Relapse (most common — average 6–7 quit attempts before sustained success), weight gain (average 5–10 lbs), mood changes, sleep disturbance. Medication side effects: NRT — skin irritation (patch), jaw soreness (gum); varenicline — nausea, vivid dreams, psychiatric symptoms (rare, FDA removed black box warning); bupropion — insomnia, seizure risk (contraindicated with seizure history).",clinicalPearls:["Smoking cessation is the ONLY intervention that slows FEV1 decline in COPD","Combining pharmacotherapy + counseling doubles quit rates","Varenicline is the most effective single-agent pharmacotherapy (~30% 12-month quit rate)","Brief interventions by RTs (even 3 minutes) increase quit attempts"],examPitfalls:["Not counseling COPD patients about smoking cessation at every visit","Recommending only willpower without pharmacotherapy — medications significantly improve success","Using bupropion in patients with seizure history — it is contraindicated"],faqJson:[{question:"Why is smoking cessation so important in COPD?",answer:"It is the ONLY intervention proven to slow the accelerated decline in FEV1 in COPD. No medication, including bronchodilators or ICS, has been shown to modify disease progression as effectively."},{question:"What is the most effective smoking cessation medication?",answer:"Varenicline (Chantix) is the most effective single agent with approximately 30% 12-month quit rate, compared to 15% for placebo. Combining it with NRT may further improve success."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["COPD Management"]},
  {slug:"copd-nutrition-management",title:"Nutritional Management in COPD",category:"COPD Management",seoTitle:"COPD Nutrition – Malnutrition, RQ & Dietary Management | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn nutritional management in COPD: respiratory quotient, malnutrition assessment, and dietary modifications for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["COPD nutrition","respiratory quotient","malnutrition","BMI","cachexia","RRT exam"],overview:"Malnutrition affects 25–40% of COPD patients and is an independent predictor of mortality. The respiratory quotient (RQ = VCO2/VO2) varies with macronutrient metabolism: carbohydrates produce the most CO2 per O2 consumed (RQ 1.0), while fats produce the least (RQ 0.7). In ventilator-dependent COPD patients, high-carbohydrate feeding can worsen hypercapnia.",mechanismPhysiology:"COPD patients are at risk for malnutrition due to: increased resting energy expenditure (15–20% higher than normal — increased work of breathing, chronic inflammation), reduced caloric intake (dyspnea interferes with eating, early satiety from hyperinflated lungs compressing the stomach), skeletal muscle wasting (systemic inflammation, disuse, hypoxia). Respiratory quotient: fat metabolism produces 0.7 CO2/O2, protein 0.8, carbohydrate 1.0, mixed diet ~0.85. Overfeeding (particularly with excess carbohydrates) increases CO2 production, potentially worsening hypercapnia and prolonging ventilator weaning.",clinicalRelevance:"Low BMI (< 21 kg/m²) is an independent predictor of mortality in COPD (BODE index component). Nutritional support improves body weight, respiratory muscle strength, exercise capacity, and quality of life. In mechanically ventilated patients, a high-fat, low-carbohydrate formula may reduce CO2 production and facilitate weaning. However, avoiding overfeeding is more important than the specific macronutrient ratio.",signsSymptoms:"Cachexia: involuntary weight loss > 5% in 6 months, BMI < 21, loss of muscle mass (temporal wasting, proximal muscle atrophy), weakness, fatigue, reduced functional capacity. Overfeeding: elevated RQ > 1.0 on indirect calorimetry, increased minute ventilation requirement, difficulty weaning from ventilator.",assessment:"BMI, weight trend over time, serum albumin and prealbumin (acute nutritional markers), handgrip strength, mid-arm muscle circumference. Indirect calorimetry: measures VO2 and VCO2 → calculates RQ and resting energy expenditure. RQ > 1.0 suggests overfeeding (lipogenesis). RQ < 0.7 suggests ketosis/starvation.",management:"Malnourished: high-calorie, nutrient-dense small meals (5–6/day), oral nutritional supplements, high-protein diet for muscle maintenance (1.2–1.5 g/kg/day). Ventilated patients: avoid overfeeding (use indirect calorimetry to guide caloric needs, typically 25–30 kcal/kg/day), moderate fat:carbohydrate ratio (40:40:20 fat:carb:protein), monitor RQ. Obesity in COPD: weight loss improves exercise tolerance and dyspnea but must be balanced against cachexia risk.",complications:"Refeeding syndrome (phosphate, potassium, magnesium depletion when feeding malnourished patients), aspiration with enteral feeding, overfeeding-related hypercapnia, further muscle wasting without intervention.",clinicalPearls:["RQ > 1.0 indicates overfeeding — the excess calories are being converted to fat, producing extra CO2","Avoid overfeeding is MORE important than reducing carbohydrate percentage in ventilated patients","BMI < 21 in COPD is an independent mortality predictor (BODE index)","Small frequent meals reduce gastric distension and diaphragmatic compression from hyperinflation"],examPitfalls:["Attributing ventilator weaning failure to carbohydrate intake without checking for overfeeding first","Not assessing nutritional status in COPD patients with weight loss","Recommending extremely low-carbohydrate diets instead of simply avoiding overfeeding"],faqJson:[{question:"Why does carbohydrate metabolism produce more CO2?",answer:"Carbohydrate oxidation has an RQ of 1.0 (1 CO2 produced per O2 consumed), while fat has 0.7 and protein 0.8. More carbohydrate metabolism increases CO2 production, which can be problematic for patients with CO2 retention."},{question:"How does malnutrition affect COPD outcomes?",answer:"Malnutrition weakens respiratory muscles, reduces exercise capacity, impairs immune function, and is an independent predictor of mortality in COPD. Nutritional support improves weight, muscle strength, and quality of life."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["COPD Management","Mechanical Ventilation"]},
  {slug:"copd-noninvasive-ventilation",title:"Nocturnal NIV in Stable COPD",category:"COPD Management",seoTitle:"Nocturnal NIV for Stable COPD – Indications & Evidence | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn about nocturnal NIV in stable hypercapnic COPD: HOT-HMV trial evidence, patient selection, and settings for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["nocturnal NIV","stable COPD","hypercapnia","HOT-HMV","chronic respiratory failure","RRT exam"],overview:"Nocturnal noninvasive ventilation (NIV) is increasingly used for stable COPD patients with persistent hypercapnia after exacerbation. The HOT-HMV trial demonstrated that adding NIV to home oxygen therapy in patients with persistent hypercapnia (PaCO2 > 53 mmHg) 2–4 weeks post-exacerbation reduced readmission and improved survival.",mechanismPhysiology:"Stable COPD patients with chronic hypercapnia develop respiratory muscle fatigue, blunted chemoreceptor sensitivity, and nocturnal hypoventilation (worsened during REM sleep when accessory muscle activity is lost). Nocturnal NIV rests respiratory muscles, improves chemoreceptor sensitivity, and augments ventilation during sleep, resulting in sustained daytime PaCO2 improvement. High-intensity NIV (targeting normalization of PaCO2 rather than just comfort) appears more effective than low-intensity approaches.",clinicalRelevance:"HOT-HMV trial (2017): patients with persistent hypercapnia (PaCO2 > 53) 2–4 weeks after acute exacerbation, adding NIV to LTOT reduced 12-month readmission (63% vs 80%) and improved time to readmission/death. Patient selection is key — NIV is for patients with PERSISTENT hypercapnia after recovery, not during the acute phase. High-intensity NIV (high IPAP targeting normal PaCO2) shows better outcomes than low-intensity settings.",signsSymptoms:"Candidates: persistent hypercapnia (PaCO2 > 53 mmHg) 2–4 weeks after exacerbation recovery, on LTOT, morning headaches (nocturnal hypoventilation), excessive daytime sleepiness, recurrent exacerbations with respiratory failure.",assessment:"Confirm persistent hypercapnia on stable ABG 2–4 weeks post-discharge. Assess for nocturnal hypoventilation (overnight SpO2 monitoring, transcutaneous CO2). Ensure patient can tolerate mask interface. Assess home environment suitability.",management:"Settings: BiPAP with backup rate. Target PaCO2 reduction toward normal (high-intensity approach): IPAP 20–30 cmH2O, EPAP 4–6 cmH2O, backup RR 14–16. Use overnight during sleep (minimum 4 hours/night). Mask selection: oronasal for nocturnal use. Follow-up ABG at 4–6 weeks. Adjust settings based on response. Continue LTOT alongside NIV.",complications:"Mask discomfort, aerophagia, air leak, skin breakdown, claustrophobia, non-adherence, central apneas (may occur with high pressures). Patient education and close follow-up improve adherence.",clinicalPearls:["HOT-HMV: NIV + LTOT reduces readmission vs LTOT alone in persistent hypercapnia post-exacerbation","High-intensity NIV (targeting PaCO2 normalization) is more effective than low-intensity comfort settings","Persistent hypercapnia must be confirmed 2–4 weeks post-discharge — not during acute phase","Minimum 4 hours/night NIV use is needed for clinical benefit"],examPitfalls:["Starting nocturnal NIV during acute exacerbation rather than after recovery with persistent hypercapnia","Using low IPAP 'comfort' settings instead of high-intensity settings targeting PaCO2 normalization","Not confirming persistent hypercapnia before initiating chronic NIV"],faqJson:[{question:"When is nocturnal NIV indicated in COPD?",answer:"For stable COPD patients with persistent hypercapnia (PaCO2 > 53 mmHg) 2–4 weeks after exacerbation recovery, who are on LTOT. The HOT-HMV trial demonstrated reduced readmission and improved survival."},{question:"What settings are used for nocturnal NIV in COPD?",answer:"High-intensity settings: IPAP 20–30 cmH2O targeting PaCO2 normalization, EPAP 4–6 cmH2O, backup RR 14–16, used during sleep for minimum 4 hours/night."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["COPD Management","Mechanical Ventilation"]},
  {slug:"copd-comorbidities",title:"COPD Comorbidities",category:"COPD Management",seoTitle:"COPD Comorbidities – Cardiovascular, Metabolic & Psychiatric | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn the major comorbidities of COPD: cardiovascular disease, osteoporosis, anxiety/depression, lung cancer, and metabolic syndrome for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["COPD comorbidities","cardiovascular","osteoporosis","anxiety","depression","lung cancer","RRT exam"],overview:"COPD rarely exists in isolation. More than 90% of COPD patients have at least one significant comorbidity, and comorbidities are the leading cause of death in mild-moderate COPD. Cardiovascular disease, osteoporosis, anxiety/depression, lung cancer, and metabolic syndrome are the most clinically significant comorbidities.",mechanismPhysiology:"Systemic inflammation in COPD (elevated CRP, IL-6, TNF-α, fibrinogen) drives extrapulmonary disease. Mechanisms: shared risk factors (smoking → COPD + CVD + lung cancer), systemic inflammation (→ atherosclerosis, insulin resistance, muscle wasting), physical inactivity (→ deconditioning, osteoporosis, depression), medications (corticosteroids → osteoporosis, hyperglycemia, myopathy), and hypoxemia (→ polycythemia, pulmonary hypertension, cognitive impairment).",clinicalRelevance:"Cardiovascular disease is the leading cause of death in GOLD 1–2 COPD. Heart failure frequently coexists (shared dyspnea symptom makes diagnosis challenging). Depression and anxiety affect 25–40% of COPD patients and are associated with worse outcomes, reduced adherence, and increased exacerbation frequency. Osteoporosis affects 35–60% of COPD patients. Screening and managing comorbidities significantly improves COPD outcomes.",signsSymptoms:"Cardiovascular: chest pain, palpitations, edema, exercise intolerance beyond expected for lung function. Depression: persistent low mood, anhedonia, sleep disturbance, social withdrawal. Anxiety: panic attacks (often confused with dyspnea), avoidance behavior. Osteoporosis: height loss, kyphosis, fragility fractures. Lung cancer: hemoptysis, weight loss, new CXR abnormality.",assessment:"Screen for comorbidities at COPD diagnosis and regularly: cardiovascular risk assessment, bone density screening (DEXA) for patients on chronic steroids or with risk factors, depression/anxiety screening (PHQ-9, GAD-7), diabetes screening (HbA1c), lung cancer screening (LDCT if meets criteria).",management:"Treat comorbidities according to standard guidelines — COPD medications generally do not interact adversely with cardiac medications. Beta-blockers: cardioselective beta-blockers (metoprolol, bisoprolol) are SAFE in COPD and should NOT be withheld for heart failure or post-MI indications. Statins: may have anti-inflammatory benefits in COPD. SSRIs/SNRIs: first-line for depression/anxiety. Pulmonary rehabilitation addresses deconditioning, anxiety, depression, and social isolation simultaneously.",complications:"Undertreated comorbidities increase mortality, reduce quality of life, and increase healthcare utilization. Polypharmacy creates medication interaction risks. Competing diagnostic symptoms (dyspnea from COPD vs heart failure) delay diagnosis.",clinicalPearls:["Cardiovascular disease, not respiratory failure, is the leading cause of death in mild-moderate COPD","Cardioselective beta-blockers are SAFE in COPD — do NOT withhold for cardiac indications","Depression and anxiety affect 25–40% of COPD patients — screen routinely","Pulmonary rehabilitation addresses multiple comorbidities: deconditioning, depression, anxiety, isolation"],examPitfalls:["Withholding beta-blockers in COPD patients with heart failure or post-MI — cardioselective agents are safe","Not screening COPD patients for depression and anxiety","Attributing all dyspnea to COPD without considering coexisting heart failure"],faqJson:[{question:"Are beta-blockers safe in COPD?",answer:"Yes — cardioselective beta-blockers (metoprolol, bisoprolol) are safe in COPD and should NOT be withheld for cardiac indications such as heart failure or post-MI. They reduce cardiovascular mortality."},{question:"What is the leading cause of death in mild-moderate COPD?",answer:"Cardiovascular disease is the leading cause of death in GOLD 1–2 COPD, not respiratory failure. This highlights the importance of cardiovascular screening and treatment in COPD patients."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["COPD Management"]},
  {slug:"copd-lung-volume-reduction",title:"Lung Volume Reduction in COPD",category:"COPD Management",seoTitle:"Lung Volume Reduction Surgery & Endobronchial Valves | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn lung volume reduction strategies for severe emphysema: LVRS, endobronchial valves, and patient selection for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["lung volume reduction","LVRS","endobronchial valves","emphysema","hyperinflation","RRT exam"],overview:"Lung volume reduction surgery (LVRS) and endobronchial valve placement are interventional treatments for select patients with severe emphysema and hyperinflation. By removing or deflating the most destroyed, hyperinflated lung tissue, these procedures improve diaphragmatic mechanics, elastic recoil, and gas exchange in the remaining healthier lung.",mechanismPhysiology:"In emphysema, destroyed alveolar tissue traps air and compresses adjacent healthier lung. Hyperinflation flattens the diaphragm, reducing its mechanical efficiency. LVRS removes 20–30% of the most affected lung tissue, reducing hyperinflation, improving diaphragm position and function, increasing elastic recoil, and improving V/Q matching. Endobronchial valves achieve similar results non-surgically — one-way valves placed in airways of targeted lobes allow air to exit but not enter, causing controlled lobar atelectasis.",clinicalRelevance:"The NETT (National Emphysema Treatment Trial) established LVRS efficacy: patients with upper-lobe-predominant emphysema and low exercise capacity benefited most (improved survival, exercise capacity, and QoL). Endobronchial valves (Zephyr valves — LIBERATE, STELVIO, IMPACT trials) provide similar benefits with lower procedural risk in patients with complete fissures and minimal collateral ventilation.",signsSymptoms:"Candidates for LVR: severe emphysema (FEV1 20–45% predicted), significant hyperinflation (TLC > 100%, RV > 150%), upper-lobe-predominant disease on CT, exercise limitation despite optimal medical therapy and pulmonary rehabilitation, non-smoking for ≥ 4 months.",assessment:"Pre-procedural: CT chest (emphysema distribution, fissure completeness for valves), full PFTs (FEV1, DLCO, RV, TLC), 6MWT, CPET, echocardiography, ABG. For endobronchial valves: Chartis assessment of collateral ventilation (valves work only with intact fissures and absence of collateral ventilation). Contraindications: FEV1 < 20% with DLCO < 20% (NETT high mortality subgroup), active smoking, severe comorbidities.",management:"LVRS: bilateral stapled lung volume reduction via VATS or median sternotomy. Endobronchial valves: bronchoscopic placement of one-way valves in target lobe airways, outpatient/1–2 day admission. Post-procedure: aggressive pulmonary rehabilitation, close monitoring for pneumothorax (occurs in 25% of valve patients within first 72 hours). Valve removal is possible if complications arise — reversible procedure.",complications:"LVRS: 30-day mortality 5–7%, prolonged air leak (most common), respiratory failure, pneumonia. Endobronchial valves: pneumothorax (25%), valve migration, infection distal to valve, COPD exacerbation, granulation tissue. High-risk group (NETT): FEV1 < 20% + DLCO < 20% → prohibitive mortality with LVRS.",clinicalPearls:["Best LVRS candidates: upper-lobe-predominant emphysema + low exercise capacity → survival benefit","Endobronchial valves require complete fissures and no collateral ventilation to work","FEV1 < 20% + DLCO < 20% = prohibitive surgical risk for LVRS (NETT high-risk group)","Pneumothorax occurs in ~25% of valve patients within 72 hours — close monitoring essential"],examPitfalls:["Recommending LVRS for patients with FEV1 < 20% AND DLCO < 20% — this group has prohibitive mortality","Not recognizing that endobronchial valves require complete fissures to be effective","Forgetting that pulmonary rehabilitation is required BEFORE and AFTER LVR procedures"],faqJson:[{question:"Who benefits most from lung volume reduction surgery?",answer:"Patients with upper-lobe-predominant emphysema and low baseline exercise capacity benefit most — the NETT trial showed improved survival, exercise capacity, and quality of life in this subgroup."},{question:"How do endobronchial valves work?",answer:"One-way valves placed in airways of targeted lobes allow trapped air and secretions to exit but prevent new air from entering, causing controlled atelectasis that reduces hyperinflation and improves diaphragm mechanics."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["COPD Management"]},

  // ═══ Asthma (9 more) ═══
  {slug:"asthma-severity-classification",title:"Asthma Severity Classification",category:"Asthma",seoTitle:"Asthma Severity – Intermittent vs Persistent Classification | RRT",seoDescription:"Classify asthma severity: intermittent, mild/moderate/severe persistent using symptoms, FEV1, and exacerbation frequency for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["asthma severity","intermittent","persistent","NAEPP","GINA classification","RRT exam"],overview:"Asthma severity classification guides initial therapy selection before treatment is started. The NAEPP Expert Panel Report and GINA guidelines use symptom frequency, nighttime symptoms, FEV1, and exacerbation risk to categorize severity into intermittent, mild persistent, moderate persistent, and severe persistent.",mechanismPhysiology:"Asthma severity represents the intrinsic intensity of the disease process. It is assessed BEFORE starting controller therapy (severity classification is different from asthma control assessment, which evaluates response TO treatment). Classification is based on the most severe feature: if any single parameter meets a higher severity category, the patient is classified at that level. Impairment domain (current symptoms) and Risk domain (future exacerbation/decline risk) are both considered.",clinicalRelevance:"Severity determines the initial step of therapy: Intermittent → Step 1 (SABA as needed). Mild persistent → Step 2 (low-dose ICS). Moderate persistent → Step 3 (low-dose ICS/LABA). Severe persistent → Step 4–5 (medium/high-dose ICS/LABA ± add-on therapies). After therapy is initiated, management is guided by asthma CONTROL (well-controlled, not well-controlled, very poorly controlled), not severity.",signsSymptoms:"Intermittent: symptoms ≤ 2 days/week, nighttime symptoms ≤ 2×/month, SABA use ≤ 2 days/week, no interference with normal activity, FEV1 > 80%, 0–1 exacerbations/year. Mild persistent: symptoms > 2 days/week but not daily, nighttime > 2×/month, minor limitation, FEV1 ≥ 80%, ≥ 2 exacerbations/year. Moderate persistent: daily symptoms, nighttime > 1×/week, some limitation, FEV1 60–80%. Severe persistent: symptoms throughout the day, nighttime often nightly, extremely limited, FEV1 < 60%.",assessment:"Use the highest severity category based on any parameter. Assess before initiating treatment. Include: symptom frequency, nighttime symptom frequency, short-acting bronchodilator use frequency, interference with normal activity, FEV1/PEF values, exacerbation history. GINA classification differs slightly and emphasizes treatment response for ongoing management.",management:"Initiate therapy at the appropriate step for the patient's severity. Reassess control in 2–6 weeks and adjust. Step up if not well-controlled (after verifying adherence, technique, and triggers). Step down if well-controlled for ≥ 3 months. The goal is to find the minimum effective therapy that maintains control.",complications:"Under-classification leads to under-treatment and increased exacerbation risk. Over-classification may result in unnecessary medication exposure. Severity may change over time — periodic reassessment is needed. Some patients with apparently intermittent asthma may have severe, life-threatening exacerbations.",clinicalPearls:["Severity is assessed BEFORE treatment; control is assessed DURING treatment","Classify based on the MOST SEVERE feature — one severe criterion overrides milder features","Even patients with intermittent asthma can have severe, life-threatening exacerbations","After initial classification, management is guided by asthma CONTROL, not severity"],examPitfalls:["Confusing severity classification (pre-treatment) with control assessment (during treatment)","Not using the most severe feature to classify — one moderate criterion with mild others = moderate","Treating based on severity alone after treatment is started rather than switching to control assessment"],faqJson:[{question:"What is the difference between asthma severity and asthma control?",answer:"Severity is the intrinsic intensity of disease assessed BEFORE starting therapy. Control evaluates how well symptoms and risks are managed WITH current therapy. Severity guides initial treatment; control guides subsequent adjustments."},{question:"What defines moderate persistent asthma?",answer:"Daily symptoms, nighttime symptoms > 1×/week (but not nightly), some limitation of activity, FEV1 60–80% predicted. Treatment: Step 3 — low-dose ICS/LABA combination."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Asthma"]},
  {slug:"exercise-induced-bronchoconstriction",title:"Exercise-Induced Bronchoconstriction",category:"Asthma",seoTitle:"Exercise-Induced Bronchoconstriction – Diagnosis & Prevention | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn EIB: pathophysiology, diagnosis with exercise challenge, prevention with SABA and ICS, and management for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["exercise induced bronchoconstriction","EIB","exercise asthma","eucapnic voluntary hyperpnea","sports asthma","RRT exam"],overview:"Exercise-induced bronchoconstriction (EIB) is transient airway narrowing occurring during or shortly after vigorous exercise. It occurs in 80–90% of asthma patients and 10–15% of the general population without asthma. EIB results from airway water loss and cooling during high-minute-ventilation exercise, triggering mast cell mediator release.",mechanismPhysiology:"During intense exercise, minute ventilation increases 10–20-fold, bypassing upper airway conditioning. This causes: (1) Osmotic theory — rapid evaporation of airway surface liquid increases osmolarity → mast cell degranulation → bronchoconstriction (predominant mechanism). (2) Thermal theory — airway cooling during exercise followed by rapid rewarming causes reactive hyperemia and edema. Bronchoconstriction typically peaks 5–10 minutes after exercise and resolves within 30–60 minutes. A refractory period of 1–3 hours may follow.",clinicalRelevance:"EIB should be suspected in any patient with cough, dyspnea, chest tightness, or wheezing with exercise. Diagnosis requires exercise challenge (treadmill or cycle with 85% max HR for 6–8 minutes) or eucapnic voluntary hyperpnea (EVH) test, with ≥ 10% fall in FEV1 confirming EIB. Prevention with SABA 15 minutes before exercise is highly effective.",signsSymptoms:"During/after exercise: cough (most common symptom), wheezing, chest tightness, dyspnea, reduced exercise performance. Symptoms typically begin 5–10 minutes after starting vigorous exercise or 5–15 minutes after stopping. Resolve within 30–60 minutes. May be worse in cold, dry air environments.",assessment:"Exercise challenge protocol: baseline spirometry → vigorous exercise at 85% predicted max HR for 6–8 minutes → serial spirometry at 5, 10, 15, 20, 30 minutes post-exercise. ≥ 10% fall in FEV1 = positive for EIB. EVH test is an alternative (more sensitive, no exercise required). Assess for underlying chronic asthma — EIB in an asthmatic suggests inadequate controller therapy.",management:"Prevention: SABA (albuterol) 2 puffs 15 minutes before exercise (protects for 2–4 hours — most effective single agent). Warm-up period (induces refractory period). For chronic athletes: daily low-dose ICS if EIB is frequent. LTRA (montelukast) provides partial protection and may be added. Non-pharmacological: nasal breathing, warm-up exercise, face mask in cold weather, avoid exercising in cold dry air or high pollen counts.",complications:"Under-recognition in athletes (attributed to 'being out of shape'), inappropriate exercise avoidance reducing fitness, rare severe bronchospasm during exercise (more likely in patients with underlying uncontrolled asthma).",clinicalPearls:["SABA 15 min before exercise is the most effective single preventive measure","Cold dry air worsens EIB — consider face mask or scarf in winter exercise","A warm-up period can induce a 1–3 hour refractory period with reduced EIB severity","If EIB is frequent, underlying asthma may be inadequately controlled — assess daily controller therapy"],examPitfalls:["Diagnosing EIB without an exercise challenge — history alone is insufficient","Not recognizing that frequent EIB may indicate inadequate asthma control requiring daily ICS","Telling patients with EIB to avoid exercise — exercise should be encouraged with proper prevention"],faqJson:[{question:"How is EIB diagnosed?",answer:"Exercise challenge test: vigorous exercise at 85% max HR for 6–8 minutes followed by serial spirometry. A fall in FEV1 ≥ 10% within 30 minutes confirms EIB."},{question:"How can EIB be prevented?",answer:"SABA 2 puffs 15 minutes before exercise is most effective. Additional measures: warm-up period, daily ICS if frequent, face mask in cold air, montelukast as adjunct."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Asthma","Pulmonary Function Testing"]},
  {slug:"asthma-medications-stepwise",title:"Asthma Stepwise Therapy",category:"Asthma",seoTitle:"Asthma Stepwise Therapy – GINA Treatment Steps | RRT Encyclopedia",seoDescription:"Master the stepwise approach to asthma management: GINA/NAEPP treatment steps, step-up/step-down criteria, and medication selection for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["asthma stepwise therapy","GINA","NAEPP","step up step down","controller therapy","RRT exam"],overview:"Asthma management follows a stepwise approach where therapy intensity is adjusted based on the patient's level of control. The goal is to achieve and maintain asthma control using the minimum effective therapy. Step-up when control is inadequate; step-down when well-controlled for ≥ 3 months.",mechanismPhysiology:"Five treatment steps with increasing intensity: Step 1 — as-needed low-dose ICS-formoterol (GINA preferred) or as-needed SABA. Step 2 — daily low-dose ICS + as-needed SABA, or as-needed ICS-formoterol. Step 3 — low-dose ICS/LABA maintenance + as-needed SABA, or maintenance and reliever therapy (MART) with ICS-formoterol. Step 4 — medium-dose ICS/LABA. Step 5 — high-dose ICS/LABA + add-on therapy (LAMA, anti-IgE, anti-IL5, anti-IL4R, low-dose OCS as last resort). GINA 2023 tracks: Track 1 (preferred) uses ICS-formoterol as both controller and reliever (MART approach).",clinicalRelevance:"Asthma is unique in that treatment must be continuously adjusted. Step-down after 3 months of good control reduces medication burden and side effects. Step-up decisions should only occur after confirming: adherence, correct technique, trigger avoidance, and correct diagnosis. Never step up without verifying these factors first. The SMART/MART approach (maintenance and reliever therapy with ICS-formoterol) simplifies treatment and improves outcomes.",signsSymptoms:"Well-controlled: symptoms ≤ 2 days/week, no nighttime symptoms, no activity limitation, SABA ≤ 2 days/week, FEV1 > 80%, no exacerbations. Not well-controlled: symptoms > 2 days/week, any nighttime symptoms, some limitation, SABA > 2 days/week, FEV1 60–80%, 1–2 exacerbations/year. Very poorly controlled: symptoms throughout the day, frequent nighttime, extremely limited, FEV1 < 60%, ≥ 3 exacerbations/year.",assessment:"Assess control at every visit using validated tools (ACT — Asthma Control Test, score ≥ 20 = well-controlled). Before stepping up: verify adherence (prescription refill records), check inhaler technique, assess trigger exposure, confirm diagnosis (consider alternative diagnoses). If truly uncontrolled: step up therapy by one step. If stepping up to Step 4–5: refer to specialist.",management:"Step-up: increase by one step. If not controlled at Step 4: specialist referral, phenotyping (eosinophilic? allergic?), consider biologics. Step-down: after ≥ 3 months well-controlled, reduce by one step. When stepping down ICS/LABA: reduce ICS dose first, then consider removing LABA (though ICS/LABA at low dose is often maintained). NEVER stop ICS entirely — even stepping down should maintain at least low-dose ICS.",complications:"Under-treatment: exacerbations, airway remodeling, fixed obstruction. Over-treatment: medication side effects (ICS — growth suppression in children, osteoporosis; LABA — tremor, tachycardia; OCS — weight gain, diabetes, osteoporosis, adrenal suppression). Failure to step down when appropriate wastes resources and increases side effect exposure.",clinicalPearls:["Before stepping up: check adherence, technique, triggers, and diagnosis — these account for most 'treatment failure'","GINA recommends ICS-formoterol as preferred reliever at ALL steps (MART approach)","Step down after 3 months of good control — the goal is minimum effective therapy","Never stop ICS entirely when stepping down — maintain at least low-dose ICS"],examPitfalls:["Stepping up therapy without checking adherence and inhaler technique first","Using SABA as the sole treatment for persistent asthma","Stopping ICS when stepping down — ICS should be maintained at minimum dose"],faqJson:[{question:"When should asthma therapy be stepped up?",answer:"Step up when asthma is not well-controlled AFTER verifying adherence, correct inhaler technique, trigger avoidance, and correct diagnosis. Increase by one step and reassess in 2–6 weeks."},{question:"When can asthma therapy be stepped down?",answer:"After ≥ 3 months of well-controlled asthma. Step down by one step, reduce ICS dose first. Never completely stop ICS. Monitor closely for loss of control."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Asthma","Pharmacology"]},
  {slug:"allergic-asthma",title:"Allergic Asthma & IgE-Mediated Disease",category:"Asthma",seoTitle:"Allergic Asthma – IgE, Allergen Triggers & Biologics | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn allergic asthma: IgE-mediated pathophysiology, common allergens, allergy testing, and anti-IgE biologic therapy for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["allergic asthma","IgE","allergen","omalizumab","atopic","allergy testing","RRT exam"],overview:"Allergic asthma is the most common asthma phenotype, accounting for 60–80% of cases. It is driven by IgE-mediated hypersensitivity to environmental allergens, resulting in Type 2 inflammation, eosinophilic airway infiltration, and characteristic features of atopy (elevated IgE, positive skin prick tests, coexisting allergic rhinitis/eczema).",mechanismPhysiology:"Allergen exposure → antigen-presenting cells activate Th2 cells → IL-4 promotes B-cell IgE class switching → IgE binds to mast cell/basophil FcεRI receptors (sensitization). On re-exposure: allergen cross-links IgE on mast cells → degranulation releasing histamine, leukotrienes, prostaglandins → early-phase response (bronchospasm within minutes). Late-phase response (4–8 hours later): eosinophil and T-cell recruitment → sustained inflammation, mucus production, airway hyperresponsiveness.",clinicalRelevance:"Common allergens: house dust mites (most common indoor allergen worldwide), pet dander (cat, dog), cockroach, mold, pollen (trees, grasses, weeds). Management includes allergen avoidance, ICS (cornerstone), and add-on therapies: leukotriene receptor antagonists (block leukotriene pathway), allergen immunotherapy (desensitization), and anti-IgE biologic (omalizumab) for moderate-severe allergic asthma uncontrolled on Step 4 therapy.",signsSymptoms:"Seasonal or perennial symptoms correlating with allergen exposure, allergic rhinitis (sneezing, nasal congestion, itchy eyes), eczema/atopic dermatitis, family history of atopy, elevated serum IgE, blood eosinophilia, positive skin prick tests or specific IgE.",assessment:"Total serum IgE (elevated in allergic asthma), specific IgE or skin prick testing to identify triggers, blood eosinophil count (typically > 300 cells/μL), FeNO (typically > 50 ppb — indicates eosinophilic inflammation). Environmental history: home environment (carpet, pets, humidity/mold, cockroaches), occupational exposures, seasonal patterns.",management:"Allergen avoidance: dust mite covers, HEPA filters, remove carpeting, reduce humidity, cockroach remediation, pet removal (or at minimum keep pets out of bedroom). Pharmacotherapy: ICS (cornerstone), LTRA (montelukast — particularly effective in aspirin-sensitive asthma), allergen immunotherapy (subcutaneous or sublingual — modifies disease course), biologics: omalizumab (anti-IgE for IgE 30–700 IU/mL with documented sensitization).",complications:"Severe allergic reactions to immunotherapy (anaphylaxis risk — must be administered in supervised setting), omalizumab injection site reactions, anaphylaxis risk with omalizumab (carry EpiPen for 24 hours post-injection), under-recognition of occupational allergen triggers.",clinicalPearls:["Allergic asthma is the most common phenotype — always assess for allergic triggers","FeNO > 50 ppb + elevated IgE + blood eosinophilia = strong allergic asthma profile","Omalizumab (anti-IgE) is indicated for moderate-severe allergic asthma with IgE 30–700 IU/mL","Dust mite allergen is the most common indoor trigger worldwide"],examPitfalls:["Not identifying allergen triggers that could be avoided or treated with immunotherapy","Prescribing omalizumab without documented allergen sensitization and appropriate IgE level","Ignoring allergic rhinitis — treating upper and lower airway disease together improves asthma control"],faqJson:[{question:"What makes allergic asthma different from other types?",answer:"Allergic asthma is driven by IgE-mediated hypersensitivity to specific allergens. It typically features elevated IgE, positive allergy tests, eosinophilic inflammation, and often coexists with allergic rhinitis and eczema."},{question:"What is omalizumab and when is it used?",answer:"Omalizumab (Xolair) is a monoclonal antibody that binds free IgE, preventing mast cell activation. It's used for moderate-severe allergic asthma uncontrolled on Step 4 therapy, with IgE 30–700 IU/mL and documented allergen sensitization."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Asthma","Pharmacology"]},
  {slug:"asthma-biologic-therapies",title:"Biologic Therapies for Severe Asthma",category:"Asthma",seoTitle:"Asthma Biologics – Anti-IgE, Anti-IL5, Anti-IL4/13 | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn biologic therapies for severe asthma: omalizumab, mepolizumab, benralizumab, dupilumab, and tezepelumab for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["asthma biologics","omalizumab","mepolizumab","dupilumab","severe asthma","monoclonal antibody","RRT exam"],overview:"Biologic therapies are monoclonal antibodies targeting specific inflammatory pathways in severe asthma. They represent a paradigm shift in treating patients with severe, uncontrolled asthma despite maximum conventional therapy. Selection is guided by the patient's inflammatory phenotype (allergic, eosinophilic, or Type 2).",mechanismPhysiology:"Available biologics: Anti-IgE — omalizumab (binds free IgE, prevents mast cell activation). Anti-IL5 — mepolizumab, reslizumab (block IL-5, reducing eosinophil production and survival). Anti-IL5R — benralizumab (binds IL-5 receptor, causes eosinophil apoptosis via ADCC). Anti-IL4Rα — dupilumab (blocks both IL-4 and IL-13 signaling). Anti-TSLP — tezepelumab (blocks thymic stromal lymphopoietin, an upstream epithelial cytokine — effective across all Type 2 phenotypes). Each targets a different point in the inflammatory cascade.",clinicalRelevance:"Biologics reduce exacerbations by 50–70%, improve lung function, and reduce or eliminate OCS need. Selection criteria: omalizumab (allergic, IgE 30–700), mepolizumab/benralizumab (eosinophils ≥ 300), dupilumab (eosinophils ≥ 300 OR FeNO ≥ 25 OR OCS-dependent), tezepelumab (broad Type 2 or even non-Type 2 inflammation). Cost: $15,000–40,000/year — reserved for severe asthma uncontrolled on Step 4/5 therapy.",signsSymptoms:"Candidates: severe asthma with ≥ 2 exacerbations/year despite Step 4/5 therapy, OCS-dependent asthma, significant impairment despite maximum conventional therapy, biomarker evidence of specific inflammatory pathway.",assessment:"Phenotype assessment before biologic selection: total IgE and specific IgE (for omalizumab), blood eosinophils (for anti-IL5 agents and dupilumab), FeNO (for dupilumab), allergen sensitization (for omalizumab). Assess: exacerbation frequency, OCS use, lung function, quality of life, and biomarker levels to guide selection.",management:"Administered as subcutaneous injections (except reslizumab — IV) at intervals of 2–8 weeks depending on agent. Assess response at 4–6 months: ≥ 50% reduction in exacerbations, reduced OCS dose, improved lung function or symptoms. If inadequate response: switch to a different biologic targeting an alternative pathway. Continue conventional therapy (ICS/LABA) alongside biologics. Step down OCS cautiously when biologic achieves control.",complications:"Injection site reactions (most common), anaphylaxis (rare — omalizumab carries highest risk, observe 2 hours first 3 doses then 30 min), helminth infection risk (eosinophil-depleting agents reduce parasite defense), cost and insurance barriers, potential for long-term unknown effects of immune pathway blockade.",clinicalPearls:["Choose biologic based on phenotype: high IgE → omalizumab, high eos → anti-IL5, mixed → dupilumab","Tezepelumab (anti-TSLP) works upstream and may benefit broader patient populations","Assess response at 4–6 months — switch agents if inadequate response","Biologics reduce but rarely eliminate the need for conventional controllers"],examPitfalls:["Prescribing biologics before confirming severe asthma on maximum conventional therapy","Choosing the wrong biologic for the patient's inflammatory phenotype","Stopping ICS/LABA when starting a biologic — conventional therapy should continue"],faqJson:[{question:"Who qualifies for biologic therapy in asthma?",answer:"Patients with severe asthma uncontrolled despite maximum Step 4/5 therapy (medium/high-dose ICS/LABA + LAMA), with ≥ 2 exacerbations/year, OCS dependence, or significant impairment, and appropriate biomarker profile."},{question:"How do you choose which biologic to use?",answer:"Based on inflammatory phenotype: allergic with elevated IgE → omalizumab; high eosinophils → mepolizumab or benralizumab; elevated eosinophils or FeNO → dupilumab; broad Type 2 → tezepelumab."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Asthma","Pharmacology"]},
  {slug:"pediatric-asthma",title:"Pediatric Asthma Management",category:"Asthma",seoTitle:"Pediatric Asthma – Diagnosis & Treatment in Children | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn pediatric asthma management: diagnosis challenges, age-appropriate therapies, device selection, and school management for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["pediatric asthma","childhood asthma","MDI spacer mask","wheezing preschooler","asthma children","RRT exam"],overview:"Asthma is the most common chronic disease in children, affecting approximately 8% of US children. Diagnosis is challenging in young children (< 5 years) who cannot perform spirometry reliably. Management follows a modified stepwise approach with age-appropriate medication delivery devices and dosing.",mechanismPhysiology:"Childhood asthma has a strong genetic and environmental component. The 'atopic march': eczema in infancy → food allergy → allergic rhinitis → asthma. Viral-induced wheeze is common in preschoolers and does not always progress to asthma. Predictors of persistent asthma (modified Asthma Predictive Index — mAPI): parental asthma, physician-diagnosed eczema, aeroallergen sensitization, ≥ 4 wheezing episodes/year, wheezing apart from colds, blood eosinophilia ≥ 4%.",clinicalRelevance:"In children < 5 years: diagnosis is clinical (pattern of wheeze, cough, dyspnea responsive to bronchodilator). Trial of controller therapy with reassessment is a valid diagnostic approach. In children ≥ 6 years: spirometry can be reliably performed. Treatment differs: ICS dosing is lower, growth monitoring is required (ICS causes ~1 cm reduction in final height — clinically insignificant), MDI+spacer+mask is the standard delivery device for young children.",signsSymptoms:"Recurrent wheeze, cough (especially nocturnal and with exercise), dyspnea, chest tightness, symptom relief with bronchodilator, symptom worsening with viral infections, exercise, cold air, allergen exposure. In young children: recurrent bronchiolitis-like episodes may represent early asthma.",assessment:"Children ≥ 6: spirometry with bronchodilator reversibility. Children < 5: clinical assessment, trial of therapy, modified Asthma Predictive Index. All ages: assess symptom frequency, nighttime awakenings, activity limitation, rescue inhaler use, exacerbation history. Allergy testing (skin prick or specific IgE) to identify triggers. Monitor growth (height) in children on ICS.",management:"Children < 5: Step 1 — as-needed SABA. Step 2 — daily low-dose ICS (nebulized budesonide or MDI+spacer+mask). Step 3 — medium-dose ICS or low-dose ICS + LTRA. Step 4 — specialist referral. Delivery: MDI+spacer+mask for ages 0–4, MDI+spacer (no mask) for ages 5–8, transition to DPI/MDI alone when technique is adequate. Children ≥ 6: similar stepwise approach to adults with age-appropriate dosing. All ages: written asthma action plan, school medication plan, annual influenza vaccination.",complications:"ICS growth effects (~1 cm reduction in adult height — clinically insignificant and outweighed by benefits), overdiagnosis in preschoolers with viral-induced wheeze (may not have persistent asthma), school absenteeism, exercise avoidance, psychosocial impact.",clinicalPearls:["MDI+spacer+mask is the standard delivery device for young children (< 5 years)","ICS causes ~1 cm reduction in final adult height — benefits far outweigh this small effect","Modified API predicts which wheezing preschoolers will develop persistent asthma","Every child with asthma needs a written action plan AND school medication plan"],examPitfalls:["Diagnosing asthma by spirometry alone in young children (< 5) who can't perform reliably","Withholding ICS in children due to growth concerns — the effect is minimal and benefits outweigh","Using a DPI in a young child who cannot generate adequate inspiratory flow"],faqJson:[{question:"How is asthma diagnosed in children under 5?",answer:"Clinical diagnosis based on pattern of recurrent wheeze, cough, and dyspnea responsive to bronchodilator. The modified Asthma Predictive Index helps identify which children will develop persistent asthma. A trial of controller therapy with reassessment is a valid approach."},{question:"Do inhaled corticosteroids affect growth in children?",answer:"ICS causes approximately 1 cm reduction in final adult height — a small, clinically insignificant effect that is far outweighed by the benefits of asthma control, exacerbation prevention, and quality of life improvement."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Asthma","Neonatal/Pediatric Respiratory Care"]},
  {slug:"asthma-copd-overlap",title:"Asthma-COPD Overlap (ACO)",category:"Asthma",seoTitle:"Asthma-COPD Overlap ACO – Diagnosis & Management | RRT",seoDescription:"Understand asthma-COPD overlap: diagnostic features, treatment approach, and clinical significance for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["asthma COPD overlap","ACO","ACOS","mixed obstructive disease","eosinophilic COPD","RRT exam"],overview:"Asthma-COPD overlap (ACO) describes patients with features of both asthma and COPD, including persistent airflow limitation (COPD feature) with variability and/or reversibility (asthma features). ACO affects approximately 15–25% of obstructive airway disease patients and is associated with more frequent exacerbations and worse quality of life than either disease alone.",mechanismPhysiology:"ACO patients share features: from asthma — eosinophilic inflammation, bronchodilator reversibility (≥ 200 mL and 12%), Type 2 biomarkers (elevated FeNO, eosinophils > 300), history of childhood asthma or atopy; from COPD — persistent airflow limitation (post-bronchodilator FEV1/FVC < 0.70), smoking history (≥ 10 pack-years), incomplete reversibility, accelerated decline. The inflammation in ACO involves both eosinophilic (asthma-type) and neutrophilic (COPD-type) pathways.",clinicalRelevance:"ACO is clinically important because: (1) ICS is more beneficial (eosinophilic component responds to steroids — unlike pure COPD); (2) LABA monotherapy is contraindicated (asthma component makes LABA-alone dangerous); (3) More frequent exacerbations than COPD alone; (4) Excluded from most clinical trials (pure COPD and pure asthma trials exclude overlap patients). Treatment requires ICS from the start, unlike step-wise COPD approach.",signsSymptoms:"Typically: onset before age 40 (asthma component) with significant smoking history (COPD component), variable but persistent dyspnea, partial bronchodilator response, atopy/allergies, frequent exacerbations, elevated eosinophils and FeNO, incomplete response to bronchodilators alone.",assessment:"Key diagnostic features: persistent airflow limitation (post-BD FEV1/FVC < 0.70) + significant bronchodilator reversibility OR marked variability + history suggesting both asthma and COPD. Blood eosinophils ≥ 300, FeNO ≥ 50 ppb, history of childhood asthma or atopy, smoking ≥ 10 pack-years, onset after age 40 but with variability/reversibility.",management:"ICS/LABA from the start — ICS addresses the eosinophilic/asthma component (unlike pure COPD where ICS is reserved for specific indications). Add LAMA for persistent symptoms. NEVER use LABA alone (asthma component). Follow asthma-guided ICS dosing. Add COPD-specific therapies (pulmonary rehabilitation, smoking cessation, vaccinations, LTOT if needed). Consider biologics for severe cases with elevated eosinophils.",complications:"Higher exacerbation rate than COPD or asthma alone, faster FEV1 decline, worse quality of life, higher healthcare utilization, under-recognition leading to inappropriate treatment (treating as pure COPD without ICS).",clinicalPearls:["ICS is needed from the START in ACO — do not follow the COPD step-wise approach","LABA monotherapy is CONTRAINDICATED in ACO — treat the asthma component with ICS/LABA","Blood eosinophils ≥ 300 + significant reversibility + smoking history = likely ACO","ACO patients have worse outcomes than either disease alone — aggressive management needed"],examPitfalls:["Treating ACO as pure COPD without ICS — the eosinophilic component requires corticosteroids","Using LABA without ICS in a patient with asthmatic features — dangerous","Not recognizing ACO as a distinct entity requiring tailored management"],faqJson:[{question:"What defines asthma-COPD overlap?",answer:"ACO combines features of both diseases: persistent airflow limitation (COPD) with significant variability/reversibility and eosinophilic inflammation (asthma), typically in a patient with smoking history and asthma features."},{question:"How does ACO treatment differ from COPD?",answer:"ACO requires ICS from the start (unlike COPD where ICS is a later addition). LABA monotherapy is contraindicated (unlike COPD where it's acceptable). Treatment follows more asthma-like ICS/LABA-centered approach."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Asthma","COPD Management"]},
  {slug:"asthma-pregnancy",title:"Asthma in Pregnancy",category:"Asthma",seoTitle:"Asthma in Pregnancy – Safe Medications & Management | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn asthma management during pregnancy: safe medications, risk of uncontrolled asthma, and monitoring for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["asthma pregnancy","ICS pregnancy","budesonide pregnancy","maternal asthma","fetal risk","RRT exam"],overview:"Asthma is the most common respiratory condition complicating pregnancy, affecting 4–8% of pregnant women. The rule of thirds applies: approximately one-third improve, one-third worsen, and one-third remain stable during pregnancy. Uncontrolled asthma poses greater risk to the fetus than the medications used to treat it.",mechanismPhysiology:"Pregnancy affects asthma through: hormonal changes (progesterone increases minute ventilation, estrogen increases mucosal edema), immunological shifts (Th2 predominance may worsen allergic/eosinophilic asthma), mechanical effects (elevated diaphragm reduces FRC), and GERD (worsens in pregnancy, triggers asthma). Uncontrolled asthma risks: maternal hypoxemia → fetal hypoxia → preeclampsia, preterm birth, low birth weight, perinatal mortality.",clinicalRelevance:"Key principle: the risk of uncontrolled asthma to the mother and fetus is GREATER than the risk of asthma medications. Budesonide is the preferred ICS (most safety data in pregnancy — FDA category B). SABA (albuterol), LABA (salmeterol/formoterol with ICS), LTRA (montelukast), and systemic steroids when needed are all considered acceptable. The stepwise approach follows the same principles as in non-pregnant patients.",signsSymptoms:"Asthma symptoms in pregnancy: dyspnea (must distinguish from physiological dyspnea of pregnancy — normal pregnancy increases RR and Vt), wheezing, cough, chest tightness. Worsening typically occurs in weeks 24–36 and improves in the last 4 weeks of pregnancy.",assessment:"Monitor PEF and FEV1 at each prenatal visit. Assess asthma control using standard tools (ACT). Check medication adherence (many women stop medications due to fetal safety concerns — this is a major cause of worsening). ABG: normal pregnancy values differ — PaCO2 30–32 mmHg, PaO2 100–105 mmHg, HCO3 20–22 mEq/L, pH 7.40–7.45 (compensated respiratory alkalosis).",management:"Continue ICS (budesonide preferred) — do NOT stop controller medications. Stepwise approach same as non-pregnant. Treat exacerbations aggressively: SABA, systemic steroids when needed (untreated exacerbation harms fetus more than a short steroid course). Avoid triggers, treat GERD, influenza vaccination. Fetal monitoring during acute exacerbations. Continue medications during labor and delivery.",complications:"Uncontrolled asthma risks: preeclampsia (25% increased risk), preterm birth, low birth weight, cesarean delivery, perinatal mortality. Medication discontinuation is the most common reason for worsening — patient education is critical.",clinicalPearls:["Uncontrolled asthma is MORE dangerous to the fetus than asthma medications","Budesonide is the preferred ICS in pregnancy (most safety data — FDA category B)","Normal pregnancy PaCO2 is 30–32 mmHg — a 'normal' PaCO2 of 40 in a pregnant patient is concerning","Do NOT stop asthma medications during pregnancy — educate patients about the risk of uncontrolled disease"],examPitfalls:["Stopping ICS in pregnancy due to fetal safety concerns — this worsens asthma and increases fetal risk","Interpreting a PaCO2 of 40 as normal in pregnancy — this represents relative hypercarbia","Under-treating asthma exacerbations in pregnancy — aggressive treatment is needed"],faqJson:[{question:"Should asthma medications be stopped during pregnancy?",answer:"No — the risk of uncontrolled asthma to the mother and fetus (preeclampsia, preterm birth, fetal hypoxia) is far greater than the risk of asthma medications. Continue controller therapy throughout pregnancy."},{question:"Which ICS is preferred in pregnancy?",answer:"Budesonide is preferred because it has the most human safety data in pregnancy (FDA category B). However, patients well-controlled on another ICS should not be switched — maintaining control is the priority."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Asthma"]},
  {slug:"asthma-occupational",title:"Occupational Asthma",category:"Asthma",seoTitle:"Occupational Asthma – Work-Related Triggers & Diagnosis | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn occupational asthma: sensitizer vs irritant-induced, diagnosis with serial PEF monitoring, and workplace management for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["occupational asthma","work-related asthma","sensitizer","isocyanates","serial PEF","RRT exam"],overview:"Occupational asthma (OA) is asthma caused or worsened by workplace exposures. It accounts for 10–25% of adult-onset asthma cases. Two types exist: sensitizer-induced OA (immunological, latency period, IgE or T-cell mediated) and irritant-induced OA (non-immunological, no latency, high-concentration irritant exposure — includes reactive airways dysfunction syndrome/RADS).",mechanismPhysiology:"Sensitizer-induced: high-molecular-weight agents (flour, animal proteins, latex) → IgE-mediated. Low-molecular-weight agents (isocyanates, wood dust, metals) → T-cell or non-IgE mechanisms. Requires latency period (weeks to years of exposure before sensitization). Once sensitized, even very low exposures trigger symptoms. Irritant-induced (RADS): single or multiple high-concentration irritant exposure → direct airway injury → persistent asthma symptoms within 24 hours, no sensitization required.",clinicalRelevance:"Common occupational sensitizers: isocyanates (paint, foam, plastics — most common cause), flour/grain dust (bakers), laboratory animal proteins, wood dust (western red cedar — plicatic acid), latex, cleaning products, metals (platinum, chromium). Early diagnosis and removal from exposure offers the best prognosis — continued exposure leads to irreversible obstruction.",signsSymptoms:"Key historical features: symptoms improve on days off/vacation and worsen during work weeks, onset temporally related to new job or new exposure, colleagues with similar symptoms. Symptoms: wheeze, cough, chest tightness, dyspnea — may develop immediately at work or delayed (4–8 hours later — evening/nighttime symptoms that lead to misdiagnosis).",assessment:"Serial PEF monitoring: record PEF at least 4 times daily for ≥ 2 weeks at work and ≥ 2 weeks away from work — ≥ 20% variability with work pattern confirms work-relatedness. Specific inhalation challenge (gold standard — controlled exposure in specialized lab). Skin prick test or specific IgE for high-molecular-weight agents. Methacholine challenge: may show increased AHR after work periods.",management:"Primary: complete avoidance of the causative agent (most important — improvement in 50% if early removal, irreversible damage if continued exposure). Respiratory protection (masks) is INSUFFICIENT for sensitizer-induced OA — complete removal is needed. Standard asthma pharmacotherapy (ICS, SABA). Workers' compensation evaluation. Workplace surveillance programs for high-risk industries. Preventive measures: exposure reduction, substitution of sensitizing agents, engineering controls.",complications:"Permanent airway obstruction if exposure continues (30% of OA patients develop fixed obstruction despite removal), job loss and financial impact, medicolegal issues, continued symptoms after removal (persistent OA in ~70% of cases), misdiagnosis delaying appropriate intervention.",clinicalPearls:["Occupational asthma should be suspected in ALL adult-onset asthma — ask about workplace exposures","Isocyanates are the most common cause of occupational asthma","Respiratory masks are NOT sufficient for sensitizer-induced OA — complete removal from exposure is needed","Serial PEF monitoring (4×/day for 2 weeks on/off work) is the key diagnostic tool"],examPitfalls:["Not asking about workplace exposures in adult-onset asthma","Recommending respiratory protection as adequate for sensitizer-induced OA — it is not sufficient","Missing delayed symptoms (evening/night) that are actually related to workplace exposure earlier in the day"],faqJson:[{question:"How is occupational asthma diagnosed?",answer:"Serial PEF monitoring (≥ 4 times daily for 2 weeks at work and 2 weeks away) showing ≥ 20% variability with work pattern. Specific inhalation challenge is the gold standard. Specific IgE or skin prick tests for high-MW agents."},{question:"What is the most important treatment for occupational asthma?",answer:"Complete removal from the causative agent is the most important intervention. Continued exposure leads to irreversible obstruction. Respiratory protection alone is insufficient for sensitizer-induced OA."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Asthma","Infection Control"]},
  {slug:"asthma-aspirin-exacerbated",title:"Aspirin-Exacerbated Respiratory Disease (AERD)",category:"Asthma",seoTitle:"AERD – Aspirin-Exacerbated Respiratory Disease | RRT Encyclopedia",seoDescription:"Learn AERD (Samter's triad): aspirin sensitivity, nasal polyposis, and asthma. Diagnosis, management, and aspirin desensitization for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["AERD","aspirin exacerbated","Samter triad","nasal polyps","leukotriene","aspirin desensitization","RRT exam"],overview:"Aspirin-exacerbated respiratory disease (AERD), formerly known as Samter's triad, is characterized by the clinical triad of asthma, nasal polyposis, and sensitivity to aspirin/NSAIDs. It is a distinct asthma phenotype driven by dysregulated leukotriene metabolism, affecting approximately 7% of adult asthmatics and up to 15% of severe asthmatics.",mechanismPhysiology:"AERD results from dysregulated arachidonic acid metabolism: COX-1 inhibition by aspirin/NSAIDs shunts arachidonic acid to the 5-lipoxygenase pathway → excessive production of cysteinyl leukotrienes (LTC4, LTD4, LTE4), which are potent bronchoconstrictors and pro-inflammatory mediators. Simultaneously, there is decreased production of protective prostaglandin E2 (PGE2). This leukotriene excess drives both the asthma and nasal polyp formation. The reaction is NOT an allergy (not IgE-mediated) — it is a pharmacological reaction to COX-1 inhibition.",clinicalRelevance:"AERD patients typically have moderate-severe asthma with recurrent nasal polyposis requiring multiple surgeries. Aspirin/NSAID reactions range from rhinorrhea and bronchospasm to severe, life-threatening attacks. COX-2 selective NSAIDs (celecoxib) are generally safe. Leukotriene receptor antagonists (montelukast) are particularly effective in this phenotype. Aspirin desensitization followed by daily aspirin maintenance can significantly improve asthma control and reduce polyp recurrence.",signsSymptoms:"Typical presentation: adult-onset asthma (usually age 20–40), progressive nasal congestion and anosmia (loss of smell), nasal polyps on exam, history of aspirin or NSAID reaction (rhinorrhea, bronchospasm, flushing, within 30 min–3 hours of ingestion). Eosinophilic inflammation is prominent.",assessment:"Clinical diagnosis based on triad: asthma + nasal polyposis + aspirin/NSAID sensitivity. Aspirin challenge test in a supervised setting can confirm the diagnosis if history is equivocal. Nasal endoscopy for polyposis. CT sinuses showing pansinusitis with polypoid disease. Elevated urinary LTE4, blood eosinophils.",management:"Avoid aspirin and all COX-1-inhibiting NSAIDs. Use acetaminophen for analgesia (safe — does not significantly inhibit COX-1 at standard doses). Leukotriene modifiers: montelukast or zileuton (5-lipoxygenase inhibitor — particularly effective in AERD). ICS/LABA for asthma control. Intranasal corticosteroids for nasal polyps. Aspirin desensitization: performed in a monitored setting, followed by daily aspirin 325–650 mg — reduces polyp recurrence, improves asthma control, reduces need for sinus surgery. Biologics: dupilumab reduces both asthma symptoms and nasal polyps in AERD.",complications:"Severe bronchospasm and anaphylactoid reactions from accidental NSAID exposure, recurrent nasal polyposis requiring multiple surgeries, anosmia, chronic sinusitis, aspirin desensitization reactions (performed in monitored setting).",clinicalPearls:["AERD is NOT an allergy — it's a pharmacological reaction to COX-1 inhibition (no IgE involvement)","Montelukast and zileuton are particularly effective in AERD — leukotriene pathway is central","Aspirin desensitization + daily aspirin maintenance reduces polyp recurrence and improves asthma","COX-2 selective NSAIDs (celecoxib) are generally safe in AERD patients"],examPitfalls:["Calling AERD an allergy — it is a pharmacological sensitivity, not IgE-mediated","Not recognizing the triad (asthma + polyps + NSAID sensitivity) as a distinct phenotype","Using aspirin or NSAIDs in a patient with known AERD without prior desensitization"],faqJson:[{question:"What is Samter's triad?",answer:"Samter's triad (now called AERD) is the clinical triad of asthma, nasal polyposis, and aspirin/NSAID sensitivity. It is driven by excessive leukotriene production and affects approximately 7% of adult asthmatics."},{question:"Is AERD an allergy to aspirin?",answer:"No — AERD is not an allergy. It is a pharmacological sensitivity caused by COX-1 inhibition that shifts arachidonic acid metabolism toward excessive leukotriene production. It is not IgE-mediated."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Asthma","Pharmacology"]},

  // ═══ ARDS (8 more) ═══
  {slug:"ards-etiology-risk-factors",title:"ARDS Etiology & Risk Factors",category:"ARDS",seoTitle:"ARDS Causes – Direct & Indirect Lung Injury Risk Factors | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn ARDS etiology: direct vs indirect causes, risk factors, and pathological stages for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["ARDS causes","direct lung injury","indirect lung injury","sepsis ARDS","pneumonia ARDS","RRT exam"],overview:"ARDS can result from direct pulmonary insults (pneumonia, aspiration, inhalation injury, contusion, drowning) or indirect extrapulmonary causes (sepsis, pancreatitis, massive transfusion, trauma, burns). Sepsis is the most common overall cause, while pneumonia is the most common direct cause. Understanding etiology guides treatment of the underlying condition.",mechanismPhysiology:"Direct lung injury: insult directly damages the alveolar epithelium — pneumonia (bacterial, viral — including COVID-19, influenza), aspiration of gastric contents, inhalation injury (smoke, toxic gases), pulmonary contusion, near-drowning. Indirect lung injury: systemic inflammation damages the pulmonary endothelium — sepsis (most common), acute pancreatitis, massive blood transfusion (TRALI), major trauma, burns, DIC. The final common pathway for both: diffuse alveolar damage with capillary leak, protein-rich edema, surfactant inactivation, and hyaline membrane formation.",clinicalRelevance:"Identifying and treating the underlying cause is as important as supportive ventilatory management. Sepsis requires antibiotics and source control. Aspiration requires pulmonary hygiene and antibiotics if bacterial superinfection. Pancreatitis requires fluid resuscitation and monitoring. TRALI requires stopping the implicated transfusion product. COVID-19 ARDS may have distinct phenotypes (L-type with preserved compliance vs H-type with classic ARDS mechanics).",signsSymptoms:"Clinical presentation varies by etiology but all develop: acute onset dyspnea, tachypnea, hypoxemia refractory to supplemental O2, bilateral infiltrates on CXR. Onset within 1 week of the causative insult. Severity correlates with the number of risk factors present — multiple risk factors dramatically increase ARDS incidence.",assessment:"Identify the underlying cause — this guides specific treatment alongside supportive care. Assess: infection source (blood cultures, sputum, urine), aspiration history, transfusion history, trauma pattern, pancreatitis markers. Apply Berlin criteria for ARDS diagnosis. Differentiate from cardiogenic pulmonary edema (echocardiography, BNP).",management:"Dual approach: (1) Treat the underlying cause — antibiotics for sepsis/pneumonia, surgical source control, stop transfusion in TRALI, treat pancreatitis. (2) Supportive care — lung-protective ventilation, prone positioning, conservative fluids, rescue therapies as needed. The underlying cause determines prognosis and duration of ARDS more than the ventilator strategy alone.",complications:"Multi-organ failure (leading cause of death), secondary infections, barotrauma, prolonged mechanical ventilation, long-term pulmonary fibrosis, neurocognitive impairment, PTSD, ICU-acquired weakness.",clinicalPearls:["Sepsis is the most common cause of ARDS overall — always search for and treat infection","Treating the underlying cause is AS IMPORTANT as supportive ventilatory care","Multiple risk factors dramatically increase ARDS incidence — patients with ≥ 2 risk factors need close monitoring","COVID-19 ARDS may present with preserved compliance initially (L-type phenotype) — traditional ARDS management still applies"],examPitfalls:["Focusing only on ventilator management without treating the underlying cause","Not screening for ARDS in high-risk patients (sepsis, aspiration, pancreatitis, massive transfusion)","Assuming all ARDS has the same etiology and management"],faqJson:[{question:"What is the most common cause of ARDS?",answer:"Sepsis is the most common overall cause of ARDS, accounting for approximately 40% of cases. Pneumonia is the most common direct pulmonary cause."},{question:"What is the difference between direct and indirect ARDS?",answer:"Direct ARDS results from insults that damage the alveolar epithelium directly (pneumonia, aspiration). Indirect ARDS results from systemic conditions that damage the pulmonary endothelium via circulating mediators (sepsis, pancreatitis)."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["ARDS","Critical Care"]},
  {slug:"ards-rescue-therapies",title:"ARDS Rescue Therapies",category:"ARDS",seoTitle:"ARDS Rescue Therapies – iNO, ECMO & Recruitment Maneuvers | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn ARDS rescue therapies: inhaled nitric oxide, ECMO, recruitment maneuvers, and inhaled prostacyclin for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["ARDS rescue","inhaled nitric oxide","ECMO","recruitment maneuver","prostacyclin","refractory hypoxemia","RRT exam"],overview:"When standard ARDS management (LPV + prone positioning + conservative fluids) fails to achieve adequate oxygenation, rescue therapies may be considered. These include inhaled pulmonary vasodilators (iNO, inhaled prostacyclin), recruitment maneuvers, and extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO). None have proven mortality benefit in ARDS (except possibly ECMO), but they serve as bridges while the underlying cause is treated.",mechanismPhysiology:"Inhaled nitric oxide (iNO): selective pulmonary vasodilator — delivered via inhalation, reaches only ventilated alveoli → vasodilates surrounding capillaries → improves V/Q matching → improves PaO2. Inactivated by hemoglobin, so no systemic vasodilation. Dose: 5–20 ppm. Inhaled prostacyclin (epoprostenol/iloprost): same selective pulmonary vasodilation mechanism, delivered via nebulization. Recruitment maneuvers: sustained inflation (30–40 cmH2O for 30–40 seconds) or incremental PEEP increases to open collapsed alveoli. ECMO: external gas exchange — blood is pumped through an oxygenator outside the body, allowing rest of injured lungs.",clinicalRelevance:"iNO: improves PaO2 in ~60% of ARDS patients but has NOT shown mortality benefit in meta-analyses. Used as a bridge while other interventions take effect. Inhaled prostacyclin: similar mechanism to iNO, easier to deliver (nebulizer), lower cost, no methemoglobin risk. Recruitment maneuvers: may transiently improve oxygenation but the ART trial showed potential harm with aggressive recruitment protocols. ECMO: the EOLIA trial showed a trend toward survival benefit; significant crossover benefit suggests true benefit exists for appropriate candidates (PaO2/FiO2 < 50 for ≥ 3 hours, or < 80 for ≥ 6 hours, or pH < 7.25 with PaCO2 ≥ 60 for ≥ 6 hours).",signsSymptoms:"Consider rescue therapies when: PaO2/FiO2 < 100 despite optimal LPV and prone positioning, SpO2 < 88% despite FiO2 1.0 and PEEP ≥ 14, refractory hypoxemia with hemodynamic instability.",assessment:"Before rescue therapies: verify LPV is optimized (Vt 6 mL/kg IBW, Pplat ≤ 30), PEEP is adequate, prone positioning has been attempted, FiO2 is maximized, consider NMBAs, rule out pneumothorax. Calculate oxygenation index (OI = MAP × FiO2 × 100 / PaO2) — OI > 40 suggests need for ECMO consideration.",management:"iNO: start at 20 ppm, titrate to lowest effective dose, monitor for methemoglobin (stop if > 5%). If no response in 1 hour, discontinue (non-responder). Wean slowly to prevent rebound pulmonary hypertension. Inhaled prostacyclin: 10,000–50,000 ng/mL via continuous nebulization. Recruitment: use cautiously — only if experienced, monitor hemodynamics closely. ECMO: VV-ECMO for respiratory failure, VA-ECMO if combined cardiac failure — requires referral to ECMO center, initiated within days of ARDS onset for best outcomes.",complications:"iNO: methemoglobinemia, rebound pulmonary hypertension on withdrawal, no mortality benefit. Recruitment maneuvers: pneumothorax, hemodynamic collapse. ECMO: bleeding (anticoagulation required), hemolysis, thrombosis, infection, limb ischemia (VA-ECMO), air embolism, mechanical failure.",clinicalPearls:["iNO improves PaO2 but NOT mortality — use as a bridge, not definitive therapy","Wean iNO slowly to prevent rebound pulmonary hypertension","ECMO should be considered early in severe ARDS (OI > 40) — late referral worsens outcomes","Aggressive recruitment maneuvers may cause harm (ART trial) — use cautiously"],examPitfalls:["Expecting iNO to improve survival — it improves oxygenation only, not mortality","Using aggressive recruitment maneuvers without monitoring hemodynamic impact","Referring for ECMO too late — early referral improves outcomes"],faqJson:[{question:"Does inhaled nitric oxide improve survival in ARDS?",answer:"No — while iNO improves PaO2 in about 60% of patients, multiple meta-analyses have shown no mortality benefit. It is used as a bridge therapy while the underlying cause is treated."},{question:"When should ECMO be considered for ARDS?",answer:"Consider ECMO referral when: PaO2/FiO2 < 50 for ≥ 3 hours, or < 80 for ≥ 6 hours, or pH < 7.25 with PaCO2 ≥ 60 for ≥ 6 hours, despite optimal conventional management including prone positioning."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["ARDS","Mechanical Ventilation","Critical Care"]},

  // ═══ Neonatal/Pediatric (10 more) ═══
  {slug:"neonatal-resuscitation-basics",title:"Neonatal Resuscitation (NRP) Basics",category:"Neonatal/Pediatric Respiratory Care",seoTitle:"Neonatal Resuscitation NRP – Algorithm & Techniques | RRT",seoDescription:"Master NRP basics: initial assessment, PPV, chest compressions, and epinephrine administration for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["neonatal resuscitation","NRP","PPV","chest compressions","newborn","Apgar","RRT exam"],overview:"Neonatal resuscitation follows the Neonatal Resuscitation Program (NRP) algorithm, a systematic approach to managing newborns who fail to transition normally at birth. Approximately 10% of newborns require some assistance, 5% require positive pressure ventilation (PPV), and < 1% require advanced interventions (compressions, intubation, medications). Respiratory therapists are key members of the neonatal resuscitation team.",mechanismPhysiology:"At birth, the transition from fetal to neonatal circulation requires: first breath (creates negative intrathoracic pressure, opens fluid-filled alveoli), surfactant (reduces surface tension, prevents alveolar collapse), increased PaO2 (triggers pulmonary vasodilation, reduces PVR), and closure of fetal shunts (ductus arteriosus, foramen ovale). Failure of any step results in: persistent fetal circulation, continued hypoxemia, bradycardia, and need for resuscitation.",clinicalRelevance:"The Golden Minute: initial assessment and first interventions should be completed within 60 seconds of birth. NRP algorithm: (1) Initial steps — warm, dry, stimulate, clear airway if needed, assess. (2) If apneic or HR < 100 → PPV. (3) If HR < 60 after 30 seconds of effective PPV → chest compressions + PPV (3:1 ratio). (4) If HR still < 60 → epinephrine (IV preferred via UVC). Effective ventilation is the MOST IMPORTANT intervention in neonatal resuscitation.",signsSymptoms:"Assessment at birth: term? good tone? breathing/crying? If YES to all → routine care. If any NO → initial steps (warm, dry, stimulate). After initial steps: HR (auscultation/pulse oximetry), respirations, tone. HR < 100 or apneic → PPV. HR < 60 despite PPV → compressions. Apgar score at 1 and 5 minutes (but does NOT guide resuscitation decisions — action is based on HR, respirations, and tone).",assessment:"Continuous assessment during resuscitation: heart rate (most important indicator of response), respirations, SpO2 (pre-ductal — right hand), chest movement with PPV. Target SpO2 by time: 1 min 60–65%, 2 min 65–70%, 3 min 70–75%, 4 min 75–80%, 5 min 80–85%, 10 min 85–95%. Do NOT target 100% SpO2 — risk of oxygen toxicity and ROP.",management:"PPV: T-piece resuscitator or self-inflating bag, initial PIP 20–25 cmH2O (30–40 for term with no response), rate 40–60/min, FiO2 21% for ≥ 35 weeks (21–30% for < 35 weeks), titrate to SpO2 targets. MR SOPA corrective steps if PPV not effective: Mask adjustment, Reposition airway, Suction, Open mouth, Pressure increase, Alternative airway. Chest compressions: 3:1 ratio (3 compressions: 1 ventilation), depth 1/3 AP diameter, two-thumb technique preferred. Epinephrine: 0.01–0.03 mg/kg IV (UVC) or 0.05–0.1 mg/kg ET (higher dose via ETT).",complications:"Hypothermia (maintain 36.5–37.5°C — use radiant warmer, plastic wrap for preterms), pneumothorax from excessive ventilation pressure, intraventricular hemorrhage (preterms — avoid rapid changes in cerebral blood flow), oxygen toxicity (avoid excessive FiO2).",clinicalPearls:["Effective ventilation is THE most important intervention in neonatal resuscitation","Start at 21% FiO2 for term newborns — titrate up based on SpO2 targets","MR SOPA: the corrective steps for ineffective PPV — Mask, Reposition, Suction, Open, Pressure, Airway","HR is the most important indicator — if it's not improving, ventilation may not be effective"],examPitfalls:["Starting with 100% O2 in term newborns — start at 21% (room air) per NRP","Performing compressions before ensuring effective ventilation — ventilation is the priority","Not knowing the SpO2 targets by minute after birth"],faqJson:[{question:"What is the most important intervention in neonatal resuscitation?",answer:"Effective positive pressure ventilation is the most critical intervention. Most newborns who require resuscitation respond to PPV alone. Compressions and medications are needed in < 1% of deliveries."},{question:"What FiO2 should be used to start neonatal resuscitation?",answer:"21% (room air) for term newborns (≥ 35 weeks). 21–30% for preterm newborns (< 35 weeks). Titrate to SpO2 targets using pre-ductal pulse oximetry (right hand)."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Neonatal/Pediatric Respiratory Care"]},
  {slug:"bronchopulmonary-dysplasia",title:"Bronchopulmonary Dysplasia (BPD)",category:"Neonatal/Pediatric Respiratory Care",seoTitle:"BPD – Bronchopulmonary Dysplasia Prevention & Management | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn BPD: pathophysiology, prevention strategies, new vs old BPD, and long-term management for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["BPD","bronchopulmonary dysplasia","chronic lung disease","neonatal","premature lungs","RRT exam"],overview:"Bronchopulmonary dysplasia (BPD) is the most common chronic lung disease of infancy, resulting from lung injury during the critical period of alveolar and vascular development in premature infants. 'New BPD' reflects developmental arrest of alveolarization rather than the fibrotic scarring of 'old BPD.' It is defined as supplemental O2 need at 36 weeks postmenstrual age.",mechanismPhysiology:"Old BPD (pre-surfactant era): severe RDS → aggressive ventilation with high pressures and FiO2 → airway injury, fibrosis, smooth muscle hypertrophy, alternating atelectasis and hyperinflation. New BPD (post-surfactant era): predominantly affects extremely preterm infants (< 28 weeks); pathology is simplified alveolar structure (fewer, larger alveoli), dysmorphic pulmonary vasculature, and minimal fibrosis. Risk factors: prematurity (most important), mechanical ventilation duration, oxygen exposure, infection/inflammation, PDA, fluid overload, genetic susceptibility.",clinicalRelevance:"BPD prevention strategies are central to respiratory therapy in the NICU: early CPAP instead of routine intubation, caffeine therapy (CAP trial showed reduced BPD), gentle ventilation strategies (volume-targeted, permissive hypercapnia), minimizing O2 exposure (target SpO2 88–94%), surfactant replacement (INSURE technique), and prevention of infection. These are all directly within the RT's practice scope.",signsSymptoms:"Persistent respiratory distress beyond the acute RDS phase, continued O2 requirement at 28 days of life or 36 weeks PMA, tachypnea, retractions, wheezing, feeding difficulties, poor weight gain. CXR: may show hyperinflation, hazy opacities, and cystic changes. Classification: mild (room air at 36 weeks PMA), moderate (< 30% FiO2), severe (≥ 30% FiO2 or positive pressure at 36 weeks).",assessment:"Defined at 36 weeks PMA: any supplemental O2 or respiratory support needed = BPD. Assess severity: mild, moderate, severe. Monitor growth (caloric needs increased 20–30% above normal), respiratory status, developmental milestones. Echocardiography for pulmonary hypertension screening.",management:"Prevention (most important): early CPAP, caffeine, gentle ventilation, minimize O2 exposure, surfactant, infection prevention, fluid restriction, vitamin A supplementation. Treatment: supplemental O2 to maintain SpO2 targets, diuretics (furosemide, chlorothiazide + spironolactone — reduce pulmonary edema), inhaled bronchodilators for airway reactivity, inhaled corticosteroids for airway inflammation (systemic steroids only for severe BPD due to neurodevelopmental concerns), nutritional support (caloric density 24–30 kcal/oz), RSV prophylaxis (palivizumab).",complications:"Pulmonary hypertension (major cause of morbidity/mortality), recurrent respiratory infections (especially RSV — can be fatal), growth failure, neurodevelopmental impairment, exercise intolerance in childhood, increased asthma risk, cor pulmonale.",clinicalPearls:["Prevention is more important than treatment — early CPAP, caffeine, and gentle ventilation reduce BPD","Caffeine (CAP trial) reduces BPD incidence and improves long-term neurodevelopment","Systemic dexamethasone for BPD may increase cerebral palsy risk — use judiciously and only for severe cases","Pulmonary hypertension screening (echocardiography) should be performed in all moderate-severe BPD"],examPitfalls:["Not recognizing that 'new BPD' is primarily developmental arrest, not fibrotic scarring","Using systemic steroids liberally for BPD without considering neurodevelopmental risks","Failing to screen for pulmonary hypertension in moderate-severe BPD"],faqJson:[{question:"What causes BPD?",answer:"BPD results from lung injury during critical alveolar development in premature infants. Risk factors include prematurity, mechanical ventilation, oxygen exposure, infection, and inflammation."},{question:"How is BPD prevented?",answer:"Early CPAP instead of routine intubation, caffeine therapy, gentle ventilation with low tidal volumes, minimizing FiO2 exposure (target SpO2 88–94%), surfactant replacement, and infection prevention."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Neonatal/Pediatric Respiratory Care"]},
  {slug:"pediatric-croup",title:"Croup (Laryngotracheobronchitis)",category:"Neonatal/Pediatric Respiratory Care",seoTitle:"Croup – Pediatric Upper Airway Emergency | RRT Encyclopedia",seoDescription:"Learn croup management: viral laryngotracheobronchitis, steeple sign, racemic epinephrine, dexamethasone for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["croup","laryngotracheobronchitis","steeple sign","racemic epinephrine","barky cough","stridor","RRT exam"],overview:"Croup (acute laryngotracheobronchitis) is the most common cause of upper airway obstruction in children aged 6 months to 6 years. Caused primarily by parainfluenza virus, it produces subglottic edema resulting in the characteristic barky (seal-like) cough, inspiratory stridor, and hoarse voice. Most cases are mild and self-limited, but severe croup requires respiratory therapy intervention.",mechanismPhysiology:"Viral infection (parainfluenza types 1 and 3 most common, also RSV, influenza, adenovirus) causes inflammation and edema of the subglottic region — the narrowest part of the pediatric airway (cricoid cartilage ring). Because pediatric airways are smaller, even modest edema significantly reduces airway diameter and increases resistance (Poiseuille's law: resistance ∝ 1/r⁴). Cool, dry air may provide symptomatic relief by reducing mucosal edema (mechanism debated). Racemic epinephrine causes local vasoconstriction, reducing mucosal edema.",clinicalRelevance:"Westley croup score assesses severity: mild (0–2): barky cough, no stridor at rest, no retractions → outpatient dexamethasone. Moderate (3–7): stridor at rest, retractions → dexamethasone + racemic epinephrine. Severe (8–17): marked stridor, severe retractions, decreased air entry, altered consciousness → dexamethasone + repeated racemic epinephrine + close monitoring for intubation. Dexamethasone (0.6 mg/kg PO/IM/IV single dose) reduces symptoms, ED revisits, and hospitalization.",signsSymptoms:"Prodrome: URI symptoms for 1–3 days. Then: sudden onset barky cough (seal-like), inspiratory stridor (worse with agitation, crying), hoarse voice, low-grade fever. Symptoms typically worse at night. Mild: no stridor at rest. Moderate: stridor at rest. Severe: stridor at rest with retractions, poor air entry, agitation or lethargy. CXR (if obtained): steeple sign (subglottic narrowing).",assessment:"Clinical diagnosis — CXR not routinely needed. Assess severity using Westley croup score. Keep child calm (agitation worsens obstruction). Monitor: stridor at rest, work of breathing, air entry, level of consciousness, SpO2. Differential diagnosis: epiglottitis (drooling, toxic appearance, thumb sign on lateral neck X-ray — rare post-Hib vaccination), foreign body aspiration, bacterial tracheitis, retropharyngeal abscess.",management:"Mild: single dose dexamethasone 0.6 mg/kg (PO/IM, max 10 mg), cool mist (evidence is weak but traditionally used), discharge home with return precautions. Moderate: dexamethasone 0.6 mg/kg + racemic epinephrine 0.5 mL of 2.25% solution nebulized (or L-epinephrine 5 mL of 1:1000). Observe for ≥ 2 hours after racemic epinephrine for rebound (symptoms may recur as effect wears off in 1–2 hours). Severe: repeated racemic epinephrine, heliox if available and FiO2 requirement allows, consider ICU for close monitoring, intubation only for impending respiratory failure (use ETT 0.5–1 mm smaller than predicted).",complications:"Rebound after racemic epinephrine (symptoms may recur as effect wears off — observe ≥ 2 hours), bacterial tracheitis (secondary bacterial infection), respiratory failure requiring intubation (rare), rarely mortality.",clinicalPearls:["Dexamethasone 0.6 mg/kg single dose is the cornerstone treatment — effective within 2–4 hours","Observe ≥ 2 hours after racemic epinephrine for rebound — effects wear off in 1–2 hours","Keep the child calm — agitation significantly worsens upper airway obstruction","If intubation is needed, use ETT 0.5–1 mm smaller than age-appropriate due to subglottic edema"],examPitfalls:["Discharging a child immediately after racemic epinephrine without observing for rebound","Not giving dexamethasone — it is effective for ALL severities of croup","Confusing croup with epiglottitis — epiglottitis features drooling, toxic appearance, and thumb sign"],faqJson:[{question:"What is the most effective treatment for croup?",answer:"Dexamethasone 0.6 mg/kg (single dose PO or IM) is the cornerstone treatment, effective for all severities. Racemic epinephrine is added for moderate-severe cases for immediate symptom relief."},{question:"Why observe after racemic epinephrine?",answer:"Racemic epinephrine's effect wears off in 1–2 hours, and symptoms may rebound. Patients must be observed for at least 2 hours after treatment to ensure stability before discharge."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Neonatal/Pediatric Respiratory Care","Airway Management"]},
  {slug:"bronchiolitis",title:"Bronchiolitis in Infants",category:"Neonatal/Pediatric Respiratory Care",seoTitle:"Bronchiolitis – RSV, Management & Supportive Care | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn infant bronchiolitis: RSV, supportive care, HFNC, when to intubate, and what NOT to do for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["bronchiolitis","RSV","respiratory syncytial virus","infant wheeze","HFNC","supportive care","RRT exam"],overview:"Bronchiolitis is the most common lower respiratory infection in infants under 2 years, most frequently caused by respiratory syncytial virus (RSV). It produces inflammation, edema, and mucus plugging of the small bronchioles. Management is primarily supportive — bronchodilators, corticosteroids, and antibiotics are NOT routinely recommended per AAP guidelines.",mechanismPhysiology:"RSV (most common cause, followed by rhinovirus, parainfluenza, metapneumovirus) infects bronchiolar epithelial cells → necrosis, inflammatory infiltrate, mucus hypersecretion → airway edema, mucus plugging, bronchiolar obstruction → air trapping, atelectasis, V/Q mismatch. Small airways in infants are easily obstructed due to their small diameter. The immune response drives most of the pathology — hence the lack of benefit from bronchodilators.",clinicalRelevance:"AAP guidelines emphasize supportive care only: supplemental O2 to maintain SpO2 ≥ 90% (continuous monitoring NOT required if clinically stable), nasal suctioning (sNRB obstruction is a major contributor to distress in obligate nose-breathing infants), adequate hydration (IV if unable to feed), and respiratory support if needed (HFNC, CPAP, or mechanical ventilation for severe cases). NOT recommended: routine albuterol, epinephrine, systemic corticosteroids, chest physiotherapy, antibiotics (unless secondary bacterial infection).",signsSymptoms:"URI prodrome (rhinorrhea, cough, low-grade fever) progressing to: tachypnea, wheezing, crackles, nasal flaring, retractions, feeding difficulty, apnea (in young infants < 2 months). Peak severity at days 3–5, resolution over 1–3 weeks. Risk factors for severe disease: age < 12 weeks, prematurity (< 35 weeks), congenital heart disease, chronic lung disease, immunodeficiency.",assessment:"Clinical diagnosis — routine CXR and viral testing are NOT recommended (do not change management). Assess: respiratory rate, work of breathing, SpO2, ability to feed, hydration status. Admit if: SpO2 < 90%, significant respiratory distress, inability to feed, apnea, age < 12 weeks, underlying cardiac/pulmonary disease, inadequate home monitoring capability.",management:"Supportive: nasal suctioning (bulb or suction catheter), supplemental O2 if SpO2 < 90%, adequate hydration (IV or nasogastric if unable to feed), positioning (upright/elevated head). Escalation: HFNC (30–40% of hospitalized bronchiolitis patients now receive HFNC — reduces ICU admission), CPAP for moderate-severe distress, mechanical ventilation for respiratory failure. Prevention: palivizumab (anti-RSV monoclonal antibody) for high-risk infants, nirsevimab (long-acting, single dose for all infants), hand hygiene, avoid sick contacts.",complications:"Apnea (especially infants < 2 months), respiratory failure requiring intubation (3–5% of hospitalized cases), secondary bacterial infection, dehydration, prolonged hospitalization in high-risk infants, recurrent wheezing in subsequent years (debated whether this represents early asthma).",clinicalPearls:["Albuterol and steroids are NOT recommended for bronchiolitis — they do not improve outcomes","HFNC has reduced ICU admission rates for bronchiolitis — consider before intubation","Nasal suctioning is one of the most effective supportive interventions — infants are obligate nose breathers","Apnea may be the presenting sign of bronchiolitis in infants < 2 months — monitor closely"],examPitfalls:["Recommending albuterol or steroids for bronchiolitis — NOT indicated per AAP guidelines","Ordering routine CXR or viral testing — these do not change management","Not recognizing apnea as a presenting feature in very young infants"],faqJson:[{question:"Why don't bronchodilators work for bronchiolitis?",answer:"Bronchiolitis pathology involves inflammatory edema and mucus plugging of small airways, not smooth muscle bronchospasm. Bronchodilators target smooth muscle and do not address the primary pathology."},{question:"When should infants with bronchiolitis be admitted?",answer:"Admission criteria: SpO2 < 90%, significant respiratory distress, inability to feed, apnea, age < 12 weeks, underlying cardiac or pulmonary disease, or inadequate home monitoring."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Neonatal/Pediatric Respiratory Care"]},
  {slug:"epiglottitis",title:"Epiglottitis",category:"Neonatal/Pediatric Respiratory Care",seoTitle:"Epiglottitis – Acute Upper Airway Emergency | RRT Encyclopedia",seoDescription:"Learn epiglottitis: clinical features, thumb sign, airway management, and why direct visualization should be avoided for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["epiglottitis","supraglottitis","thumb sign","H influenzae","upper airway obstruction","RRT exam"],overview:"Epiglottitis is an acute, potentially fatal inflammation of the epiglottis and surrounding supraglottic structures that can rapidly progress to complete airway obstruction. While dramatically reduced by Hib vaccination in children, it still occurs in unvaccinated children and increasingly in adults. It is a true airway emergency requiring immediate management.",mechanismPhysiology:"Historically caused by Haemophilus influenzae type b (Hib) — now rare in vaccinated populations. In adults and unvaccinated children, other organisms cause epiglottitis: Streptococcus, Staphylococcus, and non-typeable H. influenzae. Infection causes rapid cellulitis and edema of the epiglottis and aryepiglottic folds → progressive upper airway narrowing → potential for sudden, complete obstruction, especially with agitation or lying supine.",clinicalRelevance:"Critical points: (1) Do NOT examine the throat with a tongue depressor — this can trigger laryngospasm and complete obstruction. (2) Keep the patient calm — agitation worsens obstruction. (3) Allow the patient to maintain their preferred position (usually sitting upright, leaning forward — 'tripod' or 'sniffing' position). (4) Secure the airway in the OR with ENT/anesthesia backup BEFORE it becomes an emergency. (5) Lateral neck X-ray shows 'thumb sign' (swollen epiglottis) vs normal 'epiglottic curl.'",signsSymptoms:"Rapid onset (hours): high fever, toxic appearance, severe sore throat, dysphagia, drooling (unable to swallow secretions), muffled 'hot potato' voice, stridor, tripod positioning (sitting upright, leaning forward, mouth open, jaw thrust). Notably ABSENT: barky cough (this distinguishes from croup). Children: anxious, toxic, prefer sitting. Adults: sore throat disproportionate to pharyngeal findings.",assessment:"Clinical diagnosis — DO NOT examine the throat if epiglottitis is suspected (risk of triggering complete obstruction). If stable enough: lateral neck X-ray (thumb sign). If unstable: proceed directly to airway management. Blood cultures and epiglottic cultures (after airway is secured). Keep resuscitation equipment immediately available at all times — including tracheostomy tray.",management:"Immediate: keep patient calm, allow preferred position, supplemental O2 (blow-by if not tolerated by mask), have emergency airway equipment ready. Definitive: controlled intubation in the OR with ENT backup (in case surgical airway is needed). Pharmacology: IV antibiotics (ceftriaxone + vancomycin empirically until culture results), IV dexamethasone to reduce edema. Do NOT: lay the patient supine, examine the throat, leave the patient unattended, delay airway management.",complications:"Complete airway obstruction (rapidly fatal if not managed), respiratory arrest, cardiac arrest from hypoxia, epiglottic abscess, sepsis, death. Post-intervention: extubation typically possible within 48–72 hours after antibiotics reduce edema.",clinicalPearls:["NEVER examine the throat with a tongue depressor if epiglottitis is suspected — can trigger complete obstruction","Drooling + toxic appearance + NO barky cough = epiglottitis (not croup)","Secure airway in OR with ENT backup — do not wait for respiratory arrest","Thumb sign on lateral neck X-ray confirms the diagnosis — but do not delay airway management for imaging"],examPitfalls:["Examining the throat of a child with suspected epiglottitis — this can cause fatal obstruction","Confusing epiglottitis with croup — epiglottitis has NO barky cough, has drooling and toxic appearance","Delaying airway management to obtain imaging — airway security is the priority"],faqJson:[{question:"How is epiglottitis different from croup?",answer:"Epiglottitis: acute onset, high fever, toxic appearance, drooling, NO barky cough, thumb sign on X-ray. Croup: gradual onset, low-grade fever, barky cough, steeple sign on X-ray, non-toxic appearance."},{question:"Why shouldn't you examine the throat in suspected epiglottitis?",answer:"Using a tongue depressor or direct visualization can trigger laryngospasm and complete airway obstruction in a patient with a swollen, inflamed epiglottis. This can be rapidly fatal."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Neonatal/Pediatric Respiratory Care","Airway Management"]},

  // ═══ Airway Management (8 more) ═══
  {slug:"difficult-airway-management",title:"Difficult Airway Management",category:"Airway Management",seoTitle:"Difficult Airway – Prediction, Planning & Rescue | RRT Encyclopedia",seoDescription:"Master difficult airway management: prediction tools, LEMON assessment, supraglottic airways, and surgical airway for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["difficult airway","LEMON","Mallampati","supraglottic airway","LMA","surgical airway","RRT exam"],overview:"A difficult airway exists when a trained practitioner has difficulty with bag-mask ventilation, intubation, or both. Approximately 1–4% of all intubations are difficult, and unanticipated difficult airways account for a significant proportion of anesthesia-related deaths. Prediction, planning, and having backup strategies are essential.",mechanismPhysiology:"Difficult airway anatomy: short neck, receding chin (retrognathia), large tongue, small mouth opening (< 3 cm), limited neck extension, anterior larynx, Mallampati III–IV (only soft palate visible), neck obesity. LEMON assessment: Look externally (facial trauma, obesity, short neck), Evaluate 3-3-2 rule (3 fingers mouth opening, 3 fingers hyomental distance, 2 fingers thyromental space), Mallampati score, Obstruction (tumors, epiglottitis, angioedema), Neck mobility (C-spine immobilization, arthritis).",clinicalRelevance:"ASA/DAS difficult airway algorithms provide structured approaches: Plan A (intubation — direct or video laryngoscopy), Plan B (supraglottic airway — LMA, i-gel), Plan C (face mask ventilation — bag-valve-mask), Plan D (surgical airway — cricothyrotomy). The key principle: always have a backup plan before attempting intubation. 'Can't intubate, can't oxygenate' (CICO) is the most dangerous scenario — requires immediate surgical airway.",signsSymptoms:"Signs of difficult bag-mask ventilation (MOANS): Mask seal difficulty, Obesity, Age > 55, No teeth, Stiffness/snoring/sleep apnea. Signs of difficult intubation: Mallampati III–IV, limited mouth opening, limited neck extension, short thyromental distance, anterior larynx, history of difficult intubation.",assessment:"Pre-intubation: perform LEMON assessment on every patient. Check for difficult mask ventilation risk factors. Review prior intubation records if available. Prepare equipment: appropriate ETT, video laryngoscope, bougie/stylet, supraglottic airway (LMA size appropriate), cricothyrotomy kit. Establish a plan with the team before attempting intubation.",management:"Anticipated difficult airway: consider awake fiberoptic intubation (patient breathes spontaneously while scope is advanced through vocal cords). Unanticipated difficulty: follow algorithm — max 3 attempts at intubation → supraglottic airway → mask ventilation → surgical airway. Video laryngoscopy improves first-pass success and should be considered for all intubations, especially anticipated difficult airways. Bougie/gum elastic bougie: invaluable for anterior larynx — advance along anterior tracheal wall, feel 'clicks' over tracheal rings.",complications:"Failed intubation, esophageal intubation, dental injury, airway trauma, hypoxia between attempts, aspiration, death from CICO scenario. Time pressure: limit each attempt to 60 seconds, maintain oxygenation between attempts.",clinicalPearls:["Always have a backup plan — failed intubation drills should include supraglottic airway and surgical airway","Video laryngoscopy improves first-pass success — consider as first choice, not rescue","A bougie (gum elastic bougie) can be life-saving — learn to use it and always have it available","In CICO (can't intubate, can't oxygenate): do not delay surgical airway — needle/scalpel cricothyrotomy"],examPitfalls:["Not performing pre-intubation airway assessment (LEMON) on every patient","Making too many intubation attempts without transitioning to the backup plan","Delaying surgical airway in a true CICO scenario"],faqJson:[{question:"What is the LEMON assessment?",answer:"LEMON: Look externally (facial features), Evaluate 3-3-2 rule (mouth opening, hyomental distance), Mallampati score, Obstruction (upper airway pathology), Neck mobility. It predicts difficult intubation."},{question:"What is a CICO situation?",answer:"Can't Intubate, Can't Oxygenate — the most dangerous airway emergency. When intubation and mask/supraglottic ventilation both fail, immediate surgical airway (cricothyrotomy) is required."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Airway Management"]},
  {slug:"suctioning-airway-clearance",title:"Airway Suctioning Techniques",category:"Airway Management",seoTitle:"Airway Suctioning – Open vs Closed, Technique & Safety | RRT",seoDescription:"Master airway suctioning: open vs closed systems, catheter sizing, depth, duration, and complications for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["airway suctioning","open suction","closed suction","ETT suction","tracheal suction","RRT exam"],overview:"Airway suctioning removes secretions from the tracheobronchial tree through an artificial airway or the upper airway. It is one of the most frequently performed respiratory therapy procedures and requires proper technique to balance effective secretion removal with minimizing complications (hypoxemia, mucosal trauma, bradycardia).",mechanismPhysiology:"Open suctioning: disconnecting the patient from the ventilator, inserting a single-use catheter through the ETT/tracheostomy, applying negative pressure during withdrawal. Closed suctioning (inline suction): enclosed catheter system connected between the ventilator circuit and ETT — no disconnection required. Suction catheter size: should not exceed half the internal diameter of the ETT (formula: [ETT ID × 2] − 2 = French catheter size, or simply ETT ID ÷ 2 × multiply by 2 = Fr). Negative pressure: adults −120 to −150 mmHg, pediatrics −80 to −100 mmHg, neonates −60 to −80 mmHg.",clinicalRelevance:"Closed suctioning is preferred for: patients on high PEEP (≥ 10 cmH2O) or high FiO2 (prevents derecruitment from disconnection), patients with airborne infection precautions (reduces aerosol generation), hemodynamically unstable patients. Suctioning should be performed only when indicated (audible secretions, sawtooth waveform, increased PIP, triggered cough, visible secretions) — not on a fixed schedule.",signsSymptoms:"Indications for suctioning: audible secretions (gurgling), sawtooth pattern on ventilator flow waveform, increasing PIP without compliance change, decreasing SpO2, visible secretions in ETT, coughing. Complications: hypoxemia, bradycardia (vagal stimulation), mucosal trauma (bleeding), bronchospasm, elevated ICP, atelectasis from excessive suction duration/pressure.",assessment:"Assess need: auscultate for coarse crackles/rhonchi, check ventilator waveforms, observe secretion volume/character. Pre-oxygenate with 100% O2 for 30–60 seconds before suctioning (most ventilators have a suction button for this). Select appropriate catheter size. Verify suction pressure.",management:"Technique: pre-oxygenate → insert catheter WITHOUT suction to appropriate depth (ETT tip level — do not advance until resistance is met, as this causes mucosal trauma) → apply intermittent suction during withdrawal → limit suction pass to ≤ 10–15 seconds → re-oxygenate → assess need for additional passes → limit total passes to 2–3. Post-suction: return to prior ventilator settings, auscultate, assess secretion clearance. Normal saline instillation is NOT recommended — does not improve secretion removal and may worsen hypoxemia.",complications:"Hypoxemia (from disconnection and suction of O2), bradycardia (vagal stimulation — especially in neonates), mucosal trauma and bleeding (catheter too large or advanced too far), bronchospasm, atelectasis (excessive suction time), elevated ICP (avoid prolonged suctioning in neurological patients), infection transmission (open suctioning without proper technique).",clinicalPearls:["Catheter size should not exceed half the ETT ID — larger catheters generate excessive negative pressure","Suction only when indicated — not on a fixed schedule","Normal saline instillation is NOT recommended — does not improve secretion removal","Pre-oxygenate with 100% O2 for 30–60 seconds before each suction pass"],examPitfalls:["Using a suction catheter > half the ETT diameter — causes excessive negative pressure and atelectasis","Instilling normal saline before suctioning — this practice is no longer recommended","Suctioning on a fixed schedule rather than as indicated by assessment"],faqJson:[{question:"How do you determine suction catheter size?",answer:"The catheter should not exceed half the ETT internal diameter. Formula: (ETT ID × 2) − 2 = French size. Example: 8.0 mm ETT → 14 Fr catheter maximum."},{question:"What is the maximum suction duration?",answer:"Each suction pass should be limited to 10–15 seconds. Total number of passes should be limited to 2–3. Pre-oxygenate before and after suctioning."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Airway Management"]},

  // ═══ Pharmacology (9 more) ═══
  {slug:"mucolytics-mucokinetics",title:"Mucolytics & Mucokinetics",category:"Pharmacology",seoTitle:"Mucolytics – Acetylcysteine, Dornase Alfa & Hypertonic Saline | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn mucolytics and mucokinetics: acetylcysteine, dornase alfa, hypertonic saline mechanisms and clinical use for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["mucolytic","acetylcysteine","dornase alfa","hypertonic saline","cystic fibrosis","sputum","RRT exam"],overview:"Mucolytics and mucokinetics are medications that facilitate airway clearance by altering mucus properties. Mucolytics break down mucus structure (N-acetylcysteine cleaves disulfide bonds; dornase alfa hydrolyzes DNA in purulent secretions). Mucokinetics enhance mucus transport (hypertonic saline draws water into airways via osmosis). These agents are particularly important in cystic fibrosis and bronchiectasis management.",mechanismPhysiology:"N-acetylcysteine (NAC/Mucomyst): free sulfhydryl groups break disulfide bonds in mucus glycoproteins, reducing viscosity. Also an antioxidant and the antidote for acetaminophen overdose. Dornase alfa (Pulmozyme): recombinant human DNase — cleaves extracellular DNA released from neutrophils in purulent secretions, reducing viscosity. Hypertonic saline (3–7%): osmotically draws water into the airway surface liquid, hydrating mucus and improving mucociliary clearance. Also mildly stimulates cough.",clinicalRelevance:"Dornase alfa: FDA-approved for cystic fibrosis — reduces pulmonary exacerbations and improves FEV1 by 5–8%. NOT effective in non-CF bronchiectasis (DPSG trial showed no benefit). Hypertonic saline (7%): effective in both CF and non-CF bronchiectasis — cheap, widely available, improves mucociliary clearance. NAC: inhaled NAC is rarely used due to bronchospasm risk and lack of strong evidence for mucolysis in vivo. Oral NAC may reduce COPD exacerbations (BRONCUS, HIACE trials — modest benefit).",signsSymptoms:"Indications for mucolytic therapy: thick, tenacious secretions difficult to clear, cystic fibrosis, bronchiectasis, chronic bronchitis with mucus hypersecretion. Response: thinner secretions, more productive cough, improved spirometry, fewer exacerbations.",assessment:"Assess sputum characteristics: volume, color, viscosity, ease of expectoration. Monitor spirometry before and after initiation. In CF: FEV1 response at 1–3 months. Monitor for adverse effects (bronchospasm with NAC or hypertonic saline).",management:"Dornase alfa: 2.5 mg nebulized once daily (for CF only — use jet or vibrating mesh nebulizer). Hypertonic saline: 4 mL of 7% nebulized BID (pre-treat with bronchodilator to prevent bronchospasm). NAC nebulized: 3–5 mL of 20% solution diluted, pre-treat with bronchodilator. Oral NAC: 600 mg BID for COPD (evidence modest). Timing: mucolytics should be given before airway clearance techniques for maximum benefit.",complications:"NAC: bronchospasm (most common — pre-treat with bronchodilator), nausea, rhinorrhea, unpleasant taste/smell. Hypertonic saline: cough, bronchospasm (pre-treat with SABA), throat irritation. Dornase alfa: voice alteration, pharyngitis, rash (generally well-tolerated).",clinicalPearls:["Dornase alfa is for CF ONLY — it does NOT work in non-CF bronchiectasis","Pre-treat with bronchodilator before hypertonic saline or NAC to prevent bronchospasm","Give mucolytics BEFORE airway clearance techniques (CPT, PEP, etc.) for best effect","Hypertonic saline 7% is effective, cheap, and available for both CF and non-CF bronchiectasis"],examPitfalls:["Prescribing dornase alfa for non-CF bronchiectasis — it is not effective outside CF","Not pre-treating with bronchodilator before hypertonic saline or NAC nebulization","Confusing mucolytics (break down mucus) with expectorants (increase mucus volume/hydration)"],faqJson:[{question:"What is dornase alfa used for?",answer:"Dornase alfa (Pulmozyme) is used exclusively for cystic fibrosis. It breaks down DNA from neutrophils in purulent secretions, reducing viscosity and improving lung function."},{question:"Why pre-treat with bronchodilator before hypertonic saline?",answer:"Hypertonic saline can trigger bronchospasm through direct irritation and osmotic effects on the airway. Pre-treatment with a SABA (albuterol) prevents this potentially significant adverse effect."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Pharmacology"]},
  {slug:"systemic-corticosteroids",title:"Systemic Corticosteroids in Respiratory Disease",category:"Pharmacology",seoTitle:"Systemic Corticosteroids – Prednisone & Methylprednisolone | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn systemic corticosteroids: indications in asthma/COPD exacerbation, dosing, taper, and adverse effects for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["systemic corticosteroids","prednisone","methylprednisolone","steroid burst","COPD steroids","asthma steroids","RRT exam"],overview:"Systemic corticosteroids (oral or IV) are potent anti-inflammatory agents used for acute asthma exacerbations, COPD exacerbations, and other inflammatory respiratory conditions. They reduce airway inflammation, edema, and mucus production. While highly effective short-term, chronic use carries significant adverse effects requiring careful risk-benefit analysis.",mechanismPhysiology:"Corticosteroids bind intracellular glucocorticoid receptors → translocate to nucleus → suppress pro-inflammatory gene transcription (NF-κB pathway) and activate anti-inflammatory gene transcription. Effects: reduced eosinophils, lymphocytes, and mast cells in airways; decreased cytokine and leukotriene production; reduced vascular permeability and edema; restored β2-receptor responsiveness. Onset: 4–8 hours for anti-inflammatory effects (not immediate). Equivalent doses: prednisone 5 mg = methylprednisolone 4 mg = hydrocortisone 20 mg = dexamethasone 0.75 mg.",clinicalRelevance:"Acute asthma: systemic steroids reduce hospitalization by 25% and relapse by 50%. Dose: prednisone 40–60 mg/day for 5–7 days (no taper needed for short courses ≤ 2 weeks). COPD exacerbation: prednisone 40 mg/day for 5 days (REDUCE trial — 5 days is as effective as 14 days). Croup: dexamethasone 0.6 mg/kg single dose. Status asthmaticus: methylprednisolone 125 mg IV. ARDS: controversial — routine use not recommended; may benefit specific subgroups.",signsSymptoms:"Therapeutic response: reduced airway inflammation, improved airflow, decreased exacerbation severity and duration. Short-term side effects: hyperglycemia (common — monitor blood glucose), insomnia, mood changes, increased appetite, GI upset. Severe: adrenal crisis if chronic use stopped abruptly.",assessment:"Before starting: check blood glucose (hyperglycemia is common, especially in diabetics). During treatment: monitor glucose, mood, sleep, blood pressure. For courses > 2 weeks: taper to prevent adrenal suppression. For frequent courses (> 2/year in asthma): optimize controller therapy, consider biologics to reduce OCS need.",management:"Asthma exacerbation: prednisone 40–60 mg/day (adults) or 1–2 mg/kg/day (children, max 60 mg) for 5–7 days. COPD exacerbation: prednisone 40 mg/day for 5 days. Croup: dexamethasone 0.6 mg/kg single dose (max 10 mg). Taper: needed only for courses > 2 weeks (prevents adrenal crisis). IV alternatives: methylprednisolone 125 mg for status asthmaticus, then transition to oral.",complications:"Short-term: hyperglycemia, insomnia, mood lability, increased appetite, GI irritation, hypokalemia. Long-term (chronic use): adrenal suppression, osteoporosis, cataracts, glaucoma, skin thinning, easy bruising, weight gain (Cushingoid features), myopathy, immunosuppression, avascular necrosis, growth suppression in children. Sudden withdrawal after chronic use: adrenal crisis (hypotension, shock).",clinicalPearls:["5-day courses in COPD exacerbation are as effective as 14 days (REDUCE trial)","No taper needed for courses ≤ 2 weeks","Onset of action is 4–8 hours — give early in exacerbation management","If patient needs > 2 steroid courses/year for asthma, controller therapy needs optimization"],examPitfalls:["Using prolonged steroid courses (14 days) for COPD exacerbation when 5 days is sufficient","Not monitoring blood glucose during systemic steroid therapy","Stopping chronic steroids abruptly without tapering — risk of adrenal crisis"],faqJson:[{question:"How long should systemic steroids be given for COPD exacerbation?",answer:"5 days of prednisone 40 mg/day is the standard — the REDUCE trial showed this is as effective as 14 days with fewer side effects."},{question:"When is a steroid taper needed?",answer:"A taper is needed only for courses longer than 2 weeks to prevent adrenal insufficiency. Short courses (5–7 days) can be stopped abruptly."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Pharmacology","Asthma","COPD Management"]},
  {slug:"surfactant-therapy",title:"Exogenous Surfactant Therapy",category:"Pharmacology",seoTitle:"Surfactant Therapy – Types, Dosing & Administration | RRT",seoDescription:"Master exogenous surfactant therapy: natural vs synthetic, INSURE technique, dosing, and indications for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["surfactant therapy","beractant","poractant","calfactant","INSURE","neonatal RDS","RRT exam"],overview:"Exogenous surfactant replacement therapy is one of the most important advances in neonatal medicine, dramatically reducing mortality from respiratory distress syndrome. Natural surfactants (bovine or porcine-derived) are preferred over synthetic preparations due to superior clinical outcomes, including the presence of surfactant proteins SP-B and SP-C.",mechanismPhysiology:"Pulmonary surfactant is a complex mixture of phospholipids (primarily DPPC — dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine, ~70%) and surfactant proteins (SP-A, SP-B, SP-C, SP-D). It reduces alveolar surface tension from ~70 dyne/cm to near 0 at end-expiration, preventing alveolar collapse (LaPlace's law: P = 2T/r — smaller alveoli with high surface tension would collapse into larger ones without surfactant). Exogenous surfactant is administered via ETT and distributes across the alveolar surface, rapidly improving compliance and gas exchange.",clinicalRelevance:"Available preparations: Beractant (Survanta) — bovine-derived, 100 mg/kg dose, up to 4 doses. Calfactant (Infasurf) — bovine-derived, 105 mg/kg, up to 3 doses. Poractant alfa (Curosurf) — porcine-derived, initial dose 200 mg/kg then 100 mg/kg, up to 3 doses. Natural surfactants are superior to synthetic (contain SP-B and SP-C). The INSURE technique (Intubate, Surfactant, Extubate to CPAP) minimizes ventilator exposure and reduces BPD.",signsSymptoms:"Indications: neonatal RDS (primary indication), meconium aspiration syndrome (adjunctive), congenital pneumonia (off-label), ARDS in adults (investigational — no proven benefit). Response to surfactant: rapid improvement in compliance (within minutes), improved oxygenation (FiO2 can often be rapidly weaned), improved CXR appearance. Need for re-dosing: recurrent desaturation, increasing FiO2 requirement, worsening compliance.",assessment:"Before administration: confirm RDS diagnosis, ensure ETT is properly positioned. During administration: monitor HR, SpO2, chest rise. Administer in aliquots (typically 1/4 of dose per position — may vary by institutional protocol) with position changes to distribute surfactant to different lung regions. After administration: rapidly wean FiO2 to target SpO2 88–94%, avoid aggressive suctioning for 2–4 hours (allows surfactant to distribute and incorporate).",management:"Prophylactic (< 26 weeks GA) vs rescue (after RDS diagnosis) — current trend favors early rescue approach with CPAP. INSURE technique preferred: brief intubation for surfactant delivery → extubation to CPAP within 1 hour. Less invasive surfactant administration (LISA): surfactant delivered via thin catheter while infant breathes spontaneously on CPAP — avoids intubation entirely (emerging practice). Re-dose if persistent O2 requirement (typically 6–12 hours after initial dose).",complications:"Transient bradycardia and desaturation during administration, ETT obstruction (thick surfactant), pulmonary hemorrhage (rare — surfactant improves blood flow to previously non-perfused areas), rapid compliance improvement may cause pneumothorax if ventilator settings are not promptly adjusted.",clinicalPearls:["Natural surfactants (bovine/porcine) are superior to synthetic — contain essential SP-B and SP-C proteins","Rapidly wean FiO2 and ventilator settings after surfactant — compliance improves within minutes","Do NOT suction for 2–4 hours after surfactant administration — allows distribution and incorporation","LISA technique (surfactant via thin catheter on CPAP) may further reduce BPD compared to INSURE"],examPitfalls:["Not adjusting ventilator settings after surfactant — rapid compliance improvement can cause overdistension","Suctioning immediately after surfactant — removes the surfactant before it can distribute","Using synthetic surfactant when natural preparations are available — natural is superior"],faqJson:[{question:"What is the INSURE technique?",answer:"INSURE: Intubate briefly, administer Surfactant, Extubate to CPAP. This minimizes ventilator exposure and is associated with reduced BPD compared to continued mechanical ventilation."},{question:"Why are natural surfactants preferred over synthetic?",answer:"Natural surfactants contain surfactant proteins SP-B and SP-C, which are essential for surfactant spreading, adsorption, and function. They demonstrate superior clinical outcomes compared to protein-free synthetic preparations."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Pharmacology","Neonatal/Pediatric Respiratory Care"]},

  // ═══ Critical Care (9 more) ═══
  {slug:"shock-types-respiratory",title:"Types of Shock for Respiratory Therapists",category:"Critical Care",seoTitle:"Shock Classification – Cardiogenic, Distributive, Hypovolemic | RRT",seoDescription:"Understand the four types of shock: hemodynamic profiles, respiratory implications, and ventilator management for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["shock","cardiogenic shock","septic shock","hypovolemic","distributive","hemodynamic","RRT exam"],overview:"Shock is inadequate tissue perfusion resulting in cellular hypoxia and organ dysfunction. The four types — cardiogenic, hypovolemic, distributive (septic), and obstructive — have distinct hemodynamic profiles and respiratory management considerations. Understanding shock types is essential for respiratory therapists managing ventilated patients in the ICU.",mechanismPhysiology:"Cardiogenic: pump failure (MI, cardiomyopathy, valvular disease) → low CO, high CVP/PCWP, high SVR. Hypovolemic: volume loss (hemorrhage, dehydration) → low CO, low CVP/PCWP, high SVR. Distributive: vasodilation (sepsis, anaphylaxis, neurogenic) → high CO (initially), low SVR, low CVP/PCWP. Obstructive: mechanical obstruction to flow (PE, tamponade, tension pneumothorax) → low CO, high CVP, variable PCWP, high SVR. All types → inadequate tissue oxygen delivery → anaerobic metabolism → lactic acidosis.",clinicalRelevance:"Respiratory therapists must understand shock because: (1) Positive pressure ventilation affects hemodynamics differently in each shock type — PEEP reduces preload (harmful in hypovolemic, potentially helpful in cardiogenic). (2) Shock patients are commonly mechanically ventilated. (3) ABG interpretation in shock reveals metabolic acidosis from tissue hypoxia. (4) Understanding hemodynamic profiles guides ventilator management and anticipation of complications.",signsSymptoms:"Common to all types: tachycardia, hypotension, oliguria, altered mental status, elevated lactate, cool/mottled extremities (except distributive — warm, flushed initially). Type-specific: Cardiogenic — JVD, pulmonary edema, S3 gallop. Hypovolemic — dry mucous membranes, tachycardia, flat neck veins. Distributive — warm/flushed (early), bounding pulses, wide pulse pressure. Obstructive — JVD, muffled heart sounds (tamponade), tracheal deviation (tension pneumothorax).",assessment:"Assess: vital signs, lactate (>2 mmol/L = tissue hypoperfusion), urine output, mental status, ABG (metabolic acidosis?), echocardiography (cardiac function, tamponade), CXR (pulmonary edema, pneumothorax). Hemodynamic monitoring: CVP, CO/CI, SVR, SvO2/ScvO2. Identify the type of shock to guide appropriate treatment.",management:"Cardiogenic: inotropes (dobutamine), reduce afterload, diuretics for pulmonary edema, IABP/Impella for refractory cases. PEEP may be beneficial (reduces preload/afterload). Hypovolemic: aggressive fluid resuscitation, blood products for hemorrhage. Minimize PEEP (reduces preload further). Distributive: fluids (30 mL/kg crystalloid) → vasopressors (norepinephrine first-line) → inotropes if needed. Obstructive: treat the cause — PE (anticoagulation/thrombolysis), tamponade (pericardiocentesis), tension pneumothorax (needle decompression → chest tube).",complications:"Multi-organ failure, ARDS, DIC, renal failure, hepatic failure, death. Ventilator management must be carefully balanced with hemodynamic status — inappropriate PEEP or tidal volumes can worsen shock.",clinicalPearls:["PEEP reduces preload — beneficial in cardiogenic shock but harmful in hypovolemic","Norepinephrine is the first-line vasopressor for septic shock — not dopamine","Tension pneumothorax is immediately reversible — needle decompression is life-saving","Lactic acidosis is the hallmark of tissue hypoperfusion regardless of shock type"],examPitfalls:["Applying high PEEP to a hypovolemic shock patient — reduces preload and worsens hypotension","Using dopamine as first-line for septic shock — norepinephrine is preferred","Not recognizing tension pneumothorax as a cause of obstructive shock — it requires immediate intervention"],faqJson:[{question:"How does PEEP affect different types of shock?",answer:"PEEP reduces preload by increasing intrathoracic pressure. This is harmful in hypovolemic shock (already volume-depleted) but may benefit cardiogenic shock (reduces preload and afterload in a failing heart)."},{question:"What is the first-line vasopressor for septic shock?",answer:"Norepinephrine is the first-line vasopressor for septic shock. It provides α1-mediated vasoconstriction with modest β1 cardiac stimulation, improving MAP without excessive tachycardia."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Critical Care"]},
  {slug:"ecmo-basics",title:"ECMO (Extracorporeal Membrane Oxygenation)",category:"Critical Care",seoTitle:"ECMO – Extracorporeal Membrane Oxygenation Basics | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn ECMO fundamentals: VV vs VA, indications, circuit components, and respiratory therapist role for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["ECMO","extracorporeal membrane oxygenation","VV-ECMO","VA-ECMO","ARDS","cardiac failure","RRT exam"],overview:"Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO) provides temporary cardiopulmonary support by circulating blood through an external gas exchange device (oxygenator). VV-ECMO (veno-venous) supports gas exchange for severe respiratory failure. VA-ECMO (veno-arterial) supports both gas exchange and circulation for combined cardiorespiratory failure. ECMO serves as a bridge to recovery, transplant, or decision.",mechanismPhysiology:"Circuit components: drainage cannula (extracts venous blood), centrifugal pump (propels blood), oxygenator (gas exchange membrane — O2 in, CO2 out), heater, return cannula (returns oxygenated blood). VV-ECMO: drainage from large vein (femoral or IJ), return to right atrium — patient's heart provides circulation. VA-ECMO: drainage from right atrium, return to femoral artery (or directly to aorta in central cannulation) — circuit provides both gas exchange AND circulatory support. Sweep gas flow controls CO2 removal; FdO2 and blood flow rate control oxygenation.",clinicalRelevance:"ECMO indications: Respiratory (VV-ECMO) — severe ARDS with PaO2/FiO2 < 50–80 despite optimal conventional management (LPV + prone positioning), OI > 40, Murray lung injury score > 3.0. Cardiac (VA-ECMO) — cardiogenic shock, post-cardiotomy, bridge to transplant, massive PE, refractory cardiac arrest (eCPR). Contraindications: irreversible underlying disease, severe neurological injury, prolonged high-pressure ventilation > 10 days. Respiratory therapists on ECMO teams manage ventilator settings, gas exchange monitoring, and circuit components.",signsSymptoms:"Candidates: refractory hypoxemia despite maximal support, worsening despite all conventional and rescue therapies, reversible underlying cause or transplant candidacy. On ECMO: ventilator settings are reduced to 'rest settings' (Vt 4–6 mL/kg, RR 10, FiO2 0.21–0.40, PEEP 10) to allow lung healing while ECMO provides gas exchange.",assessment:"Pre-ECMO: confirm appropriateness (reversible cause or transplant candidate), assess contraindications, imaging (echocardiography, CT), labs (coagulation, organ function). On ECMO: monitor circuit pressures, pump flow, oxygenator function, patient ABG vs post-oxygenator blood gas, anticoagulation (ACT or anti-Xa), hemolysis markers (plasma-free hemoglobin, LDH), daily assessment of lung recovery for potential decannulation.",management:"VV-ECMO: target SaO2 80–95% (complete normalization not necessary), adjust sweep gas for PaCO2. VA-ECMO: target adequate perfusion (lactate, SvO2). 'Rest settings' on ventilator — allow lung healing. Anticoagulation: continuous heparin targeting ACT 180–220 seconds or anti-Xa 0.3–0.7. Weaning: trial of reduced ECMO support with increased ventilator support — if tolerated (stable gas exchange, hemodynamics), decannulation is considered.",complications:"Hemorrhage (most common — anticoagulation required), thrombosis (circuit or patient), hemolysis, infection, limb ischemia (VA-ECMO arterial cannula), Harlequin syndrome (VA-ECMO: differential oxygenation — upper body may receive deoxygenated blood from native heart if cardiac function partially recovers), air embolism, renal failure, neurological events.",clinicalPearls:["ECMO is a bridge (to recovery, transplant, or decision) — not a destination therapy","VV-ECMO for lungs only, VA-ECMO for heart ± lungs","On ECMO, ventilator settings are reduced to 'rest settings' — let the lungs heal","Refer early — late ECMO referral (after > 7–10 days of high-pressure ventilation) worsens outcomes"],examPitfalls:["Confusing VV-ECMO (respiratory support only) with VA-ECMO (cardiopulmonary support)","Not understanding that ECMO patients may have low SpO2 (SaO2 80–95% is acceptable on VV-ECMO)","Maintaining aggressive ventilator settings while on ECMO — rest the lungs"],faqJson:[{question:"What is the difference between VV and VA ECMO?",answer:"VV-ECMO (veno-venous) provides gas exchange support only — the patient's heart must maintain circulation. VA-ECMO (veno-arterial) provides both gas exchange and circulatory support."},{question:"What ventilator settings are used during ECMO?",answer:"'Rest settings': low Vt (4–6 mL/kg), low RR (10), low FiO2 (0.21–0.40), moderate PEEP (10). The goal is to minimize ventilator-induced lung injury while ECMO provides gas exchange."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Critical Care","ARDS","Mechanical Ventilation"]},

  // ═══ Sleep Medicine (6 more) ═══
  {slug:"polysomnography-basics",title:"Polysomnography (Sleep Study) Basics",category:"Sleep Medicine",seoTitle:"Polysomnography PSG – Sleep Study Components & Scoring | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn polysomnography: EEG, EMG, EOG, respiratory channels, sleep staging, and scoring rules for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["polysomnography","PSG","sleep study","EEG","sleep staging","AHI","RRT exam"],overview:"Polysomnography (PSG) is the gold standard diagnostic test for sleep-disordered breathing. It simultaneously records multiple physiological parameters during sleep including brain activity, eye movements, muscle activity, respiratory effort, airflow, oxygen saturation, cardiac rhythm, and body position. Respiratory therapists may be involved in performing and scoring PSG studies.",mechanismPhysiology:"PSG channels: EEG (electroencephalography — brain wave activity for sleep staging), EOG (electrooculography — eye movements for REM identification), EMG (electromyography — chin for muscle tone, legs for movement disorders), airflow (nasal pressure transducer + oronasal thermistor), respiratory effort (thoracic and abdominal bands — inductance plethysmography), SpO2, ECG, body position sensor, snoring microphone. Sleep stages: N1 (light sleep), N2 (intermediate), N3 (deep/slow-wave sleep), REM (rapid eye movement — dreaming sleep). Sleep cycles repeat every ~90 minutes.",clinicalRelevance:"PSG is indicated for: suspected OSA (gold standard diagnosis), suspected CSA, CPAP titration (determining optimal pressure), treatment-emergent CSA evaluation, suspected narcolepsy (followed by MSLT), REM behavior disorder, periodic limb movement disorder, and unexplained hypersomnia. Home sleep apnea testing (HSAT) is an acceptable alternative for uncomplicated suspected moderate-severe OSA in patients without significant comorbidities.",signsSymptoms:"Not directly applicable — PSG is a diagnostic test. It quantifies: AHI (apnea-hypopnea index), oxygen desaturation index (ODI), minimum SpO2, time below SpO2 90%, arousal index, sleep efficiency, sleep stage distribution, periodic limb movements.",assessment:"Scoring rules (AASM criteria): Apnea — ≥ 90% reduction in airflow for ≥ 10 seconds. Hypopnea — ≥ 30% reduction in airflow for ≥ 10 seconds with ≥ 3% O2 desaturation or arousal. Classify as obstructive (effort present), central (no effort), or mixed. Calculate AHI = (apneas + hypopneas) / hours of sleep. Calculate RDI = (apneas + hypopneas + RERAs) / hours of sleep.",management:"Based on AHI: Mild OSA (5–14) → consider CPAP, oral appliance, positional therapy, weight loss. Moderate OSA (15–29) → CPAP (strongly recommended), oral appliance if CPAP intolerant. Severe OSA (≥ 30) → CPAP (essential), surgical options for select patients. Split-night study: first half diagnostic, second half CPAP titration (if AHI ≥ 40 in first 2 hours). CPAP titration: start at 4 cmH2O, increase by 1–2 cmH2O to eliminate apneas, hypopneas, and snoring in all sleep positions and stages.",complications:"PSG is non-invasive and safe. First-night effect: sleep may be fragmented due to unfamiliar environment, potentially underestimating AHI. Technical issues: lead displacement, signal artifact, patient discomfort.",clinicalPearls:["Split-night study: diagnostic first half → CPAP titration second half if AHI ≥ 40 in first 2 hours","AASM hypopnea rule: ≥ 30% airflow reduction + ≥ 3% desaturation or arousal","REM-related OSA is common — AHI may be higher in REM due to muscle atonia","Home sleep testing (HSAT) is acceptable for uncomplicated suspected moderate-severe OSA"],examPitfalls:["Not knowing the difference between apnea (≥ 90% flow reduction) and hypopnea (≥ 30% reduction)","Confusing AHI with RDI — RDI includes RERAs, AHI does not","Not recognizing that supine and REM sleep typically produce the highest AHI"],faqJson:[{question:"What does a polysomnography measure?",answer:"PSG simultaneously records: brain activity (EEG), eye movements (EOG), muscle activity (EMG), airflow, respiratory effort, oxygen saturation, ECG, body position, and snoring during sleep."},{question:"What is the difference between a full PSG and HSAT?",answer:"Full PSG is attended in a sleep lab with all channels including EEG for sleep staging. HSAT is unattended at home with limited channels — it cannot stage sleep and may underestimate AHI."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Sleep Medicine"]},
  {slug:"cpap-titration-troubleshooting",title:"CPAP Titration & Troubleshooting",category:"Sleep Medicine",seoTitle:"CPAP Titration – Pressure Settings & Troubleshooting | RRT",seoDescription:"Master CPAP titration: optimal pressure determination, auto-PAP, mask selection, and common compliance issues for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["CPAP titration","auto-PAP","APAP","mask fitting","CPAP compliance","pressure adjustment","RRT exam"],overview:"CPAP titration determines the optimal pressure that eliminates obstructive events across all sleep stages and positions. It can be performed during an attended PSG (gold standard), split-night study, or using auto-titrating PAP (APAP) at home. Troubleshooting CPAP issues is a key respiratory therapy competency, as adherence is the primary challenge.",mechanismPhysiology:"CPAP creates a pneumatic splint that holds the upper airway open during sleep. Optimal pressure is the lowest pressure that eliminates: apneas, hypopneas, respiratory effort-related arousals (RERAs), and snoring in all sleep positions and stages (including REM supine — typically requires the highest pressure). Auto-PAP (APAP) uses algorithms to detect and respond to flow limitation in real-time, auto-adjusting pressure between a set range (typically 4–20 cmH2O).",clinicalRelevance:"Lab titration protocol (AASM): start at 4 cmH2O → increase by ≥ 1 cmH2O at intervals ≥ 5 minutes to eliminate obstructive events → optimal pressure achieved when events eliminated in all stages/positions. APAP at home: acceptable initial approach for most OSA patients — eliminates need for separate titration study, reduces wait times. Download data at follow-up to verify: 95th percentile pressure (set as fixed CPAP if converting), leak data, residual AHI, usage hours.",signsSymptoms:"Common CPAP problems: mask leak (most common — causes eye irritation, mouth dryness, noise, pressure loss), mouth leak (nasal mask users — add chin strap or switch to full-face mask), claustrophobia, aerophagia (swallowing air — reduce pressure, try EPR/pressure relief), nasal congestion (add heated humidification, try nasal steroid), skin irritation/pressure sores (mask fit adjustment, try different mask style), rain-out (water in tubing — adjust humidity, use heated tubing).",assessment:"Follow-up assessment (at 1–4 weeks, then 3 months): download device data — check usage (target ≥ 4 hours/night on ≥ 70% of nights for insurance compliance), residual AHI (target < 5), leak rates (target < 24 L/min mean), 95th percentile pressure. Assess: mask fit, skin integrity, symptom improvement (ESS score reduction), sleep quality.",management:"Mask selection (most important factor for compliance): nasal mask (preferred — most comfortable, least leak), nasal pillows (minimal contact, good for claustrophobia), full-face mask (required for mouth breathers or nasal obstruction). Pressure comfort features: EPR/C-Flex (expiratory pressure relief — reduces pressure during exhalation), ramp (gradually increases pressure over 15–45 minutes at sleep onset). Heated humidification: reduces nasal dryness, congestion, and improves comfort. If compliance poor: identify the barrier (discomfort, claustrophobia, leak, aerophagia, noise) and address specifically.",complications:"CPAP non-adherence (40–60% of patients — the primary challenge), mask pressure sores (bridge of nose), conjunctivitis from mask leak, aerophagia, nasal congestion/rhinorrhea, claustrophobia, noise complaints (from patient or bed partner). Treatment-emergent central sleep apnea (5–15% of CPAP users — usually resolves within 1–3 months).",clinicalPearls:["Mask fit is the #1 determinant of CPAP adherence — spend time getting this right","APAP eliminates the need for lab titration in most uncomplicated OSA patients","Insurance compliance threshold: ≥ 4 hours/night on ≥ 70% of nights during a 30-day period","Heated humidification significantly improves comfort and adherence — use it routinely"],examPitfalls:["Using a nasal mask for a mouth breather without adding a chin strap or switching to full-face mask","Not checking for mask leak as a cause of therapy failure","Setting CPAP too high initially — causes aerophagia, discomfort, and reduces adherence"],faqJson:[{question:"What is the difference between CPAP and APAP?",answer:"CPAP delivers one fixed pressure all night. APAP auto-adjusts pressure within a set range based on real-time airflow analysis, providing the minimum effective pressure at each moment."},{question:"What constitutes CPAP compliance?",answer:"Insurance compliance requires ≥ 4 hours of use per night on ≥ 70% of nights during a consecutive 30-day period. Clinical benefit increases with more use."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Sleep Medicine"]},

  // ═══ Pulmonary Rehabilitation (4 more) ═══
  {slug:"breathing-retraining-techniques",title:"Breathing Retraining Techniques",category:"Pulmonary Rehabilitation",seoTitle:"Breathing Techniques – PLB, Diaphragmatic Breathing | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn breathing retraining: pursed-lip breathing, diaphragmatic breathing, pacing, and energy conservation for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["pursed lip breathing","diaphragmatic breathing","breathing retraining","energy conservation","dyspnea management","RRT exam"],overview:"Breathing retraining techniques help patients with chronic lung disease reduce dyspnea, improve ventilation efficiency, and enhance functional capacity. Pursed-lip breathing (PLB) and diaphragmatic breathing are the most commonly taught techniques in pulmonary rehabilitation programs.",mechanismPhysiology:"Pursed-lip breathing (PLB): exhaling through pursed lips (as if blowing out a candle) creates back pressure that splints the airways open during exhalation, preventing premature airway closure and air trapping. This effectively creates positive expiratory pressure (2–5 cmH2O), similar to PEEP. Benefits: slower respiratory rate, larger tidal volume, improved ventilation efficiency, reduced dyspnea, improved SpO2 during exertion. Diaphragmatic breathing: consciously engaging the diaphragm during inspiration while relaxing the accessory muscles. Patient places one hand on the chest and one on the abdomen — goal is abdominal movement with minimal chest wall movement.",clinicalRelevance:"PLB is highly effective and easily taught — patients often discover it independently. It is particularly beneficial in COPD where dynamic airway collapse causes air trapping. Diaphragmatic breathing has more limited evidence — it may increase work of breathing in some severe COPD patients who have already adapted to accessory muscle use. However, it remains useful for anxiety-related hyperventilation, mild-moderate COPD, and post-operative patients.",signsSymptoms:"Effective PLB: slower RR, increased Vt, decreased dyspnea, improved SpO2. Effective diaphragmatic breathing: reduced accessory muscle use, more relaxed breathing pattern, decreased anxiety-related hyperventilation.",assessment:"Assess breathing pattern before and after instruction. Monitor: respiratory rate, SpO2, dyspnea score (Borg scale), use of accessory muscles, thoracoabdominal coordination. Have patient demonstrate technique — correct errors in real-time. Assess functional improvement: can the patient perform ADLs with less dyspnea using the technique?",management:"PLB instruction: inhale through the nose for 2 counts → exhale through pursed lips for 4 counts (2:1 or 1:2 ratio). Practice at rest first, then during activity. Diaphragmatic breathing: supine position initially (gravity assists diaphragm descent), hand on abdomen rises with inhalation, hand on chest stays still. Progress to sitting, then standing, then during activity. Combine with energy conservation techniques: pacing activities, using adaptive equipment, planning rest periods, prioritizing activities.",complications:"Diaphragmatic breathing may paradoxically increase dyspnea in severe COPD patients with a flat diaphragm — if this occurs, focus on PLB instead. Over-focus on breathing technique can increase anxiety in some patients. Some patients may hyperventilate during breathing retraining sessions.",clinicalPearls:["PLB creates ~2–5 cmH2O of positive expiratory pressure — essentially 'portable PEEP'","Diaphragmatic breathing may not be appropriate for severe COPD — PLB is more universally beneficial","Combine breathing techniques with pacing and energy conservation for maximum functional improvement","Practice at rest first, then during light activity, then during more demanding activities"],examPitfalls:["Teaching only diaphragmatic breathing in severe COPD — PLB is more universally effective","Not recognizing that some patients intuitively use PLB — reinforce and refine rather than reteach","Expecting breathing retraining alone to resolve dyspnea without addressing underlying disease management"],faqJson:[{question:"How does pursed-lip breathing help COPD patients?",answer:"PLB creates back pressure (~2–5 cmH2O) that splints airways open during exhalation, preventing premature closure and air trapping. This improves gas exchange, slows breathing rate, increases tidal volume, and reduces dyspnea."},{question:"Is diaphragmatic breathing effective for all COPD patients?",answer:"Not necessarily — patients with severe COPD and a flat diaphragm may find diaphragmatic breathing increases work of breathing. PLB is more universally effective. Diaphragmatic breathing works better for mild-moderate disease and anxiety-related breathing patterns."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Pulmonary Rehabilitation","COPD Management"]},
  {slug:"airway-clearance-techniques",title:"Airway Clearance Techniques",category:"Pulmonary Rehabilitation",seoTitle:"Airway Clearance – CPT, PEP, OPEP & Vest Therapy | RRT",seoDescription:"Master airway clearance techniques: chest physiotherapy, postural drainage, PEP therapy, oscillatory PEP, and high-frequency chest wall oscillation for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["airway clearance","CPT","chest physiotherapy","PEP","flutter valve","Acapella","vest therapy","RRT exam"],overview:"Airway clearance techniques (ACTs) facilitate removal of secretions from the airways in patients with impaired mucociliary clearance. They are essential in cystic fibrosis, bronchiectasis, neuromuscular disease, and other conditions with chronic secretion retention. Multiple techniques are available, and selection should be individualized based on patient preference, effectiveness, and independence.",mechanismPhysiology:"Mechanisms for secretion mobilization: (1) Gravity-assisted drainage (postural drainage) — positioning body segments to allow gravity to move secretions from peripheral to central airways. (2) Application of force to chest wall (percussion, vibration) — loosens adherent secretions. (3) Oscillation of airflow (OPEP devices, HFCWO) — creates vibration within airways that shears mucus from airway walls. (4) Positive expiratory pressure (PEP) — splints airways open during exhalation, preventing closure and promoting collateral ventilation behind mucus plugs. (5) Controlled cough/huff — high-velocity airflow propels mobilized secretions toward the mouth.",clinicalRelevance:"Conventional CPT (postural drainage, percussion, vibration): effective but requires trained caregiver, time-consuming (30–45 min per session), position-dependent (multiple positions). PEP devices (Acapella, Flutter, Aerobika): patient-independent, portable, combine positive pressure with oscillation, can be used with nebulizer. HFCWO (The Vest/SmartVest): inflatable vest with oscillating air pulses at 5–25 Hz — hands-free, standardized treatment. Active cycle of breathing technique (ACBT): combines breathing control, thoracic expansion, and forced expiratory technique (huff).",signsSymptoms:"Indications for ACT: excessive secretion production (>25–30 mL/day), difficulty clearing secretions (weak cough, neuromuscular disease), cystic fibrosis (standard of care), bronchiectasis, atelectasis from mucus plugging, post-operative pulmonary complications, ventilated patients with thick secretions.",assessment:"Assess: sputum volume and character, cough effectiveness, chest auscultation (crackles, rhonchi), SpO2, CXR (atelectasis, infiltrate from retained secretions), patient's ability to perform technique independently. Evaluate effectiveness: improved auscultation, increased sputum expectoration, improved SpO2, resolution of atelectasis on CXR.",management:"Selection considerations: CF patients should learn multiple techniques for variety and situation-specific use. Typical regimen: 2–4 times daily, 15–30 minutes per session, before meals (reduce aspiration risk). Combine with: mucolytics (give BEFORE ACT), bronchodilators (give BEFORE or DURING ACT), and adequate hydration. OPEP devices: exhale against resistance through the device at slightly higher than normal Vt, 10–20 breaths, then huff/cough, repeat 3–4 cycles per session.",complications:"Desaturation during postural drainage (position-dependent), hemoptysis (stop percussion if significant), rib fracture (osteoporotic patients — avoid vigorous percussion), gastroesophageal reflux (avoid post-prandial, head-down positions), bronchospasm (pre-treat with bronchodilator), increased ICP (avoid Trendelenburg in neurological patients).",clinicalPearls:["Give mucolytics BEFORE ACT for maximum benefit — loosen secretions first, then mobilize","PEP/OPEP devices allow patient independence — important for long-term compliance","Avoid postural drainage positions that cause desaturation or GERD — modify positioning as needed","HFCWO (vest) provides standardized treatment without need for a caregiver — good for home use"],examPitfalls:["Performing CPT after meals — increases aspiration and GERD risk","Not pre-treating with bronchodilator before ACT in patients prone to bronchospasm","Using vigorous percussion in osteoporotic patients — risk of rib fracture"],faqJson:[{question:"What airway clearance techniques are available?",answer:"Options include: conventional CPT (postural drainage, percussion, vibration), PEP devices (Acapella, Flutter, Aerobika), HFCWO (vest therapy), ACBT, autogenic drainage, and mechanical insufflation-exsufflation (cough assist)."},{question:"When should airway clearance be performed?",answer:"Typically 2–4 times daily, before meals (not after). Give mucolytics and bronchodilators before ACT sessions for maximum benefit."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Pulmonary Rehabilitation","COPD Management"]},

  // ═══ Infection Control (3 more) ═══
  {slug:"ventilator-circuit-care",title:"Ventilator Circuit & Equipment Processing",category:"Infection Control",seoTitle:"Ventilator Circuit Care – Infection Prevention | RRT Encyclopedia",seoDescription:"Learn ventilator circuit management: when to change circuits, condensation management, and equipment processing for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["ventilator circuit","circuit change","condensation","equipment processing","infection prevention","RRT exam"],overview:"Proper ventilator circuit management is essential for infection prevention and patient safety. Evidence-based practice has shifted from routine scheduled circuit changes to changing only when visibly soiled or malfunctioning. Understanding circuit condensation management, HME vs heated humidifier considerations, and equipment processing standards is critical for respiratory therapists.",mechanismPhysiology:"Ventilator circuits become colonized with bacteria within 24 hours of use. However, circuit colonization does NOT correlate with VAP risk — the route of infection is aspiration of oropharyngeal secretions past the ETT cuff, not from the circuit. Routine circuit changes actually INCREASE VAP risk by breaking the closed system and introducing handling contamination. Condensation (rain-out): temperature differentials between heated humidifier output and ambient air cause water to condense in the circuit — this condensate can harbor bacteria and should be drained away from the patient, not back into the humidifier.",clinicalRelevance:"Evidence-based circuit management: change circuits only when visibly soiled or malfunctioning — NOT on a routine schedule. Drain condensate regularly toward the collection trap (AWAY from patient). Use closed-suction systems to maintain circuit integrity. HME: change every 24–48 hours per manufacturer recommendation. Heated humidifier water: change per institutional protocol, use closed fill systems when possible. Between-patient processing: high-level disinfection or sterilization of reusable circuits; single-use circuits are increasingly common.",signsSymptoms:"Signs requiring circuit intervention: visible soiling (blood, secretions, emesis in circuit), circuit leak (audible or measured on ventilator), excessive condensation causing flow obstruction, HME saturation (increased resistance), damaged or cracked components.",assessment:"Circuit assessment: check connections (secure, no leak), inspect for condensation (drain away from patient), check HME for saturation (increased resistance indicated by rising PIP without compliance change), verify heated wire function (if equipped — reduces rain-out). Equipment processing: verify cleaning, disinfection, and sterilization per institutional protocol and manufacturer guidelines.",management:"Daily: inspect circuit integrity, drain condensate, change HME if applicable (every 24–48 hours). As needed: change circuit if soiled/damaged. Between patients: high-level disinfection (chemical or pasteurization) for reusable circuits, or use single-patient-use disposable circuits. Nebulizer circuits: change every 24 hours or per protocol. In-line suction catheters: change every 72 hours or per protocol. Heated humidifier chambers and tubing: change per institutional protocol.",complications:"VAP risk from improper circuit handling, contaminated condensate aspiration, equipment malfunction from poor maintenance, cross-contamination between patients from improperly processed equipment.",clinicalPearls:["Do NOT change ventilator circuits on a routine schedule — only when visibly soiled (reduces VAP risk)","Drain condensate AWAY from the patient toward the collection trap","HME is contraindicated in patients with thick copious secretions or high minute ventilation (>10 L/min)","Closed suction systems reduce circuit breaks and may reduce infection risk"],examPitfalls:["Routinely changing ventilator circuits on a schedule — this increases VAP risk","Draining condensate back into the humidifier — it is contaminated","Not changing HME when it becomes saturated — increases airway resistance"],faqJson:[{question:"How often should ventilator circuits be changed?",answer:"Only when visibly soiled or malfunctioning — NOT on a routine schedule. Evidence shows that routine circuit changes increase VAP risk without clinical benefit."},{question:"Which direction should circuit condensate be drained?",answer:"Always drain condensate AWAY from the patient toward the collection trap or drain it out of the circuit. Never drain toward the patient (aspiration risk) or back into the humidifier (contamination)."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Infection Control","Mechanical Ventilation"]},

  // ═══ Patient Assessment (3 more) ═══
  {slug:"patient-history-respiratory",title:"Respiratory Patient History Taking",category:"Patient Assessment",seoTitle:"Respiratory History – Key Questions & Clinical Reasoning | RRT",seoDescription:"Learn respiratory history taking: chief complaint, HPI, smoking history, occupational exposure, and medication history for the RRT exam.",seoKeywords:["respiratory history","chief complaint","smoking history","occupational exposure","dyspnea assessment","RRT exam"],overview:"A thorough respiratory history is the foundation of clinical assessment and often provides more diagnostic information than any single test. Key components include: chief complaint, history of present illness (onset, duration, severity, triggers), past medical/surgical history, medication history, smoking/substance history, occupational/environmental exposures, and family history.",mechanismPhysiology:"The respiratory history gathers information about: temporal pattern (acute vs chronic, progressive vs episodic), symptom character (dyspnea, cough, sputum, wheezing, hemoptysis, chest pain), precipitating/relieving factors, functional limitation, risk factors (smoking, occupational exposures, family history), and response to prior treatments. Pack-year history: packs per day × years smoked. Dyspnea assessment: MRC (Medical Research Council) dyspnea scale grades 1–5, or Borg scale 0–10.",clinicalRelevance:"History guides differential diagnosis: acute dyspnea → PE, pneumothorax, asthma, HF; chronic progressive → COPD, ILD, HF; episodic → asthma, anaphylaxis. Sputum characteristics: purulent (infection), bloody (TB, cancer, PE, bronchiectasis), pink frothy (pulmonary edema), rust-colored (pneumococcal pneumonia). Occupational history identifies avoidable triggers (occupational asthma, pneumoconiosis, mesothelioma). Medication history: beta-blockers can trigger bronchospasm, ACE inhibitors cause cough, prior steroid courses indicate severity.",signsSymptoms:"Key symptoms to assess: Dyspnea — onset, severity, timing, position-dependence (orthopnea, PND), exercise tolerance. Cough — dry vs productive, timing, triggers, duration. Sputum — amount, color, consistency, blood. Wheezing — timing, triggers. Hemoptysis — amount, frequency, associated symptoms. Chest pain — pleuritic vs non-pleuritic, location, radiation.",assessment:"Systematic approach: (1) Chief complaint in patient's own words. (2) HPI using OPQRST or similar framework (Onset, Provocation/Palliation, Quality, Radiation/Region, Severity, Timing). (3) Past medical history — prior intubations, hospitalizations, surgeries. (4) Medications — all current and recent, including inhalers, OTC, and supplements. (5) Allergies — medication and environmental. (6) Social history — smoking (pack-years, cessation date), alcohol, drugs, occupation, living situation. (7) Family history — COPD, asthma, cystic fibrosis, α1-antitrypsin deficiency, lung cancer. (8) Review of systems — systemic symptoms (fever, weight loss, night sweats).",management:"History findings direct diagnostic workup: smoking + chronic dyspnea → spirometry for COPD. Episodic wheeze + triggers → spirometry with reversibility for asthma. Occupational exposure + dyspnea → occupational health assessment, PFTs, imaging. Hemoptysis + weight loss → CT chest, bronchoscopy. History also guides treatment: prior successful treatments, prior adverse reactions, patient preferences and goals.",complications:"Incomplete history: missed diagnoses, inappropriate treatment, failure to identify reversible causes. Sensitive topics: patients may underreport smoking, substance use, or occupational exposures — use non-judgmental, open-ended questions.",clinicalPearls:["Pack-year history is the standard measure of cumulative tobacco exposure: packs/day × years","OPQRST is a useful mnemonic for HPI: Onset, Provocation, Quality, Radiation, Severity, Timing","Always ask about occupational exposures in adult-onset dyspnea — occupational lung disease is common","Prior intubation history is essential — it identifies patients at higher risk for future respiratory failure"],examPitfalls:["Not calculating pack-year history — it quantifies smoking exposure risk","Forgetting to ask about occupational exposures in adult-onset respiratory symptoms","Not reviewing the medication list for respiratory side effects (ACE-I cough, beta-blocker bronchospasm)"],faqJson:[{question:"What is a pack-year?",answer:"A pack-year is a unit of smoking exposure calculated as: number of packs smoked per day × number of years smoked. For example, 1 pack/day for 20 years = 20 pack-years."},{question:"Why is occupational history important in respiratory assessment?",answer:"Occupational exposures are responsible for 10–25% of adult-onset asthma and many cases of interstitial lung disease, mesothelioma, and COPD. Identifying the exposure is essential for treatment and prevention."}],relatedLessonIds:[],relatedQuestionIds:["Patient Assessment"]},
];
